# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alexei-kosygin
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The **1965 Soviet economic reform**, sometimes called the **Kosygin reform** (Russian: Косыгинская реформа) or **Liberman reform**, named after E.G.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Liberman, was a set of planned changes in the economy of the USSR.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] A centerpiece of these changes was the introduction of profitability and sales as the two key indicators of enterprise success.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Some of an enterprise's profits would go to three funds, used to reward workers and expand operations; most would go to the central budget.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The reforms were introduced politically by Alexei Kosygin—who had just become Premier of the Soviet Union following the removal of Nikita Khrushchev—and ratified by the Central Committee in September 1965.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] They reflected some long-simmering wishes of the USSR's mathematically-oriented economic planners, and initiated the shift towards increased decentralization in the process of economic planning.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The reforms, coinciding with the Eighth Five-Year Plan, led to continued growth of the Soviet economy.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The success of said reforms was short-lived, and with the events of Prague in 1968, fueled by Moscow's implementation of the reforms in Eastern Bloc countries, led to the reforms being curtailed.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Economists like Lev Gatovsky and Liberman were instrumental in framing the theoretical underpinnings of the Soviet economic reforms of the 1960s, advocating for the use of profit motives and market mechanisms within a socialist framework.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Under Lenin, the New Economic Policy had allowed and used the concepts of profit and incentives for regulation of the Soviet economy.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Stalin transformed this policy rapidly with the collectivization of farms and nationalization of industry, which was the result of the acceleration of central planning as exemplified by the "Five-Year Plans".
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Since about 1930, the Soviet Union had used a centralized system to manage its economy.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] In this system, a single bureaucracy created economic plans, which assigned workers to jobs, set wages, dictated resource allocation, established the levels of trade with other countries, and planned the course of technological progress.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Retail prices for consumer goods were fixed at levels intended for market clearing.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The prices of wholesale goods were fixed, also, but these served an accounting function more than a market mechanism.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Collective farms also paid centrally determined prices for the supplies they needed, and unlike other sectors their workers received wages directly dependent on the profitability of the operation.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Although Soviet enterprises were theoretically governed by the principle of *khozraschet* (Russian: хозрасчёт, lit.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] 'business bookkeeping', or "accounting")—which required them to meet planners' expectations within the system of set prices for their inputs and outputs—they had little control over the biggest decisions affecting their operations.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Managers did have a responsibility to plan future gross output, which they chronically underestimated in order to later exceed the prediction.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The managers then received bonuses (*premia*) for surplus product regardless of whether it was produced in a cost-effective manner or whether their enterprise was profitable overall.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The bonuses for output came in amounts sometimes equal to the managers' base salaries.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The system also incentivized pointless increases in the size, weight, and cost of production outputs, simply because "more" had been produced.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The economic reforms emerged during a period of great ideological debate over economic planning.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] More mathematical, "cybernetic", viewpoints were at first considered deviant from orthodox Marxist economics, which considered the value of goods to derive strictly from labor.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] This doctrine, elaborated in such works as Stalin's 1952 book, *Economic Problems of Socialism in the USSR*, described the price system as a capitalist relic which would eventually disappear from communist society.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Nevertheless, computerized economics gained an important role for top planners, even while conventional Marxist–Leninist political economy was taught in most schools and promoted for public consumption.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The rising influence of statistical planning in the Soviet economy was reflected in the creation of the Central Economic Mathematical Institute (Центральный экономико-математический институт; TSEMI), led by Vasily Sergeevich Nemchinov.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Nemchinov, along with linear programming inventor Leonid Kantorovich and investment analyst Viktor Valentinovich Novozhilov, received the Lenin Prize in 1965.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The battle between "optimal" planning and convention planning raged throughout the 1960s.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Another tendency in economic planning emphasized "normative value of processing", or the importance of needs and wants in evaluating the value of production.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Major changes throughout the Soviet world became possible in 1964 with the ousting of Nikita Khrushchev and the rise of Alexei Kosygin and Leonid Brezhnev.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Economic policy was a significant area of retrospective anti-Khrushchev criticism in the Soviet press.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] This 'reformist' economic tendency in the Soviet Union had corollaries and some mutual reinforcement in Eastern Europe.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Kosygin criticized the inefficiency and inertia of economic policy under the previous administration.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] He presented a plan, including the ideas expressed by Liberman and Nemchinov, to the Communist Party Central Committee Plenum in September 1965.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The Central Committee's acceptance of the plan became crucial for practical implementation of theoretical ideas.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] According to official rationale for the reform, the increasing complexity of economic relations reduced the efficacy of economic planning and therefore reduced economic growth.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] It was recognized that the existing system of planning did not motivate enterprises to reach high rates of production or to introduce organizational or technical innovations.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Given more freedom to deviate publicly from party orthodoxy, newspapers offered new proposals for the Soviet economy.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Antonov published an article in *Izvestia* on November 22, 1961, with the title "For All and For Oneself"—advocating more power for enterprise directors.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] A widely publicized economic rationale for reform came from Evsei Liberman of the Kharkov Institute of Engineering and Economics.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] An article by Liberman on this topic, titled "Plans, Profits, and Bonuses" appeared in *Pravda* in September 1962.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Liberman, influenced by the economic "optimizers", argued for the (re)introduction of profitability as a core economic indicator.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] These proposals were controversial, and criticized especially as regressions towards a capitalist economic system.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Critics also argued that reliance on profitability would skew the proportions in which different goods were produced.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Unlike Liberman in 1962, Trapeznikov suggested that the need for reform had been embraced by party decisionmakers and would soon become a reality.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] In the following month, *Pravda* published six more articles from academicians, planners, and managers advocating reform.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Several economic experiments were initiated to test Liberman's proposals.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] These began in 1964 with new policies for two garment factories: the Bolshevichka in Moscow and the Mayak in Gorky.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] When operations at the garment factories proved tolerably successful, the experiment was expanded to about 400 other enterprises, mostly in large cities.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] One experiment in Lviv involved a coal mine and factories producing clothing, shoes, and heavy lifting equipment.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The coal mine, in particular, reportedly became more profitable after shifting to a system using bonuses and more independent decisionmaking.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Some of the experimental plants ran into problems, however, due to the unreliability of suppliers continuing to operate on the old system.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The Mayak plant faced a dilemma in trying to implement the centrally mandated experimental reforms, while simultaneously receiving contradictory orders from the local *sovnarkhoz* (regional council).
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The reform was administered by the Central Committee of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union and the Council of Ministers.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The number of policy targets was reduced from 30 to 9 (the rest remained indicators).
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Enterprises were required to determine the detailed range and variety of products, using their own funds to invest in production, establish long-term contractual arrangements with suppliers and customers and to determine the number of personnel.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Key importance was attributed to the integral indicators of economic efficiency of production — profits and profitability.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] There was the opportunity to create a number of funds based on the expense of profits — funds for the development of production, material incentives, housing, etc.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The enterprise was allowed to use the funds at its discretion.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Pricing: Wholesale sales prices would be recalibrated to reflect costs and encourage economic efficiency.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The most important changes resulting from the Liberman/Kosygin reforms involved the role of profit in the Soviet economic system.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] *Rentabelnost'* ("profitability", Russian: рентабельность) and *realizatsiya* ("sales", Russian: реализация) became the twin success indicators for enterprises.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] *Rentabelnost'* was defined in terms of the *ratio* between profits and capital, while *realizatsiya* (also meaning "implementation") depended on the total volume of sales.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Success by these measurements led to the allocation of money to a fund, which could be disbursed according to a pre-defined sequence.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The funds first went to pay for capital—including interest paid to *Gosbank*, the State Bank.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Then, they went to the new incentive funds.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Finally, they could be used by an enterprise to expand its capital for operations.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Any profit extending above the maximum for spending would go to the central budget.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The production development fund (PDF): A 'development' fund for the overall organization.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Formerly, bonuses had come from the same fund as wages.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Now, enterprise managers had slightly more discretion over how to allocate them.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] They could move some amounts of money between the bonus fund and the social welfare fund.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] They also had more power to influence wages by classifying different workers.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] In practice, the bonuses had the greatest impact on the payment of elite personnel (technicians and "employees" as opposed to "workers"), thereby counteracting the effect of Khrushchev-era wage reforms.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] An experimental system introduced at some enterprises offered extra bonuses for specific achievements—not just as a portion of total profits.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] For example, engineers using fuel more efficiently (during a shortage) could receive large premia calculated as a percentage of the money they saved.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Along with more direct responsibility for the wage fund, enterprises also gained the power to fire workers.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] In fact, the reform gave new incentive for layoffs, which in some cases could increase profitability.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] (When these occurred, the workers did not have a 'social safety net' in place in the form of unemployment insurance and career assistance).
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] To encourage accurate planning, enterprises now would be punished for performing below *or above* their planned goals.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Enterprises would also pay rent for land and natural resources.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The rationale for this practice was economic optimization.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] For example, land of differing quality required different inputs of manpower to achieve the same outputs, and thus should factor differently into the budget of an enterprise.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Bank loans, to be repaid later with interest, would be used to fund more investment projects—to incentive the careful use of funds and the speedy creation of profit.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Five different interest rates would be set, ranging from preferential to normal to punitive.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] An additional capital charge—i.e., tax—would be assessed for each enterprise based on the capital it retained: working capital, equipment, and surplus stocks.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Enterprises were to submit annual plans, called *tekhpromfinplans (from Russian: техпромфинплан (ru:Техпрофинплан) - technical and financial production plan)*, stipulating production plans by quarter and month.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Higher-ups would then approve these plans (or not) and allocate supplies and money.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The enterprise then sells its products, within the constraints of the plan.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] It is empowered to reject or return (within ten days) unneeded inputs to the supplier.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The key change which represented "decentralization" was the delegation of responsibility over modernization investments.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] However, modernization plans remained subject to central approval, as well as approval from the bank which lent the money.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The amount of development expected under these auspices fell far short of expectations, as the necessary labour and materials were simply undersupplied.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] One response to this problem in 1969 was to shift more incentives to the contractors.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] For the "optimal planners" this limited decentralization was inadequate, and the new importance assigned to "profit" was incomplete because enterprises did not control enough of the factors which might affect it.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] These councils spelled the end of a short-lived phase of worker control over production, which the Bolsheviks regarded as inefficient.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Under the New Economic Policy beginning in 1921, enterprises were classified based on their relative interdependence (and necessity to war production) or autonomy (i.e. those "endowed with complete financial and commercial independence").
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The many enterprises in the latter category were not nationalized, but instead placed under the guidance of the VSNKh, with the plan to group them into "trusts" based on production chains or geographic proximity.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] This model underwent various reorganizations, including the strengthening of *edinonachalie*, control of production units by a single manager.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] These single managers at times controlled a wide range of production activities within a single area.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The economic reform of 1957 reintroduced the *sovnarkhozy*, 104 in number, to govern production by region.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Where applicable, these corresponded closely with the boundaries of the *oblasty* (political jurisdictions).
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Complaints immediately arose that these councils did not optimize overall production chains, due to their regional focus, and that they conflicted with the authority of *Gosplan*.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] In 1962, the 104 *sovnarkhozy* were consolidated into 47 larger jurisdictions (one of which controlled all of Uzbekistan, Turkmenistan, Tadzhikistan, and Kirgizia).
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] However, by 1962–1963, the *sovnarkhozy* were becoming subordinate to numerous other agencies and organizations.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Gosplan was to be stripped of its planning authority in favor of a revitalized VSNKh.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Kosygin took aim at these "outdated forms of management" and included in his 1965 speech a return to ministries as core administrators.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] His plan resembled the ministry system under Stalin, but with a smaller number: nine all-Union ministries organized by industry (e.g., Ministry of Light Industry, Ministry of the Radio Industry, Ministry of the Chemical Industry) and eleven supervising operations within each union-republic.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The latter regional agencies reported both to the local council and to the central ministry with jurisdiction over their production type.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Gosplan had the responsibility for creating annual and long-term plans, and for guiding development and resource management.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] *Gossnab* became the primary coordinator of material-technical supply, and was charged with large-scale analysis (possibly using computers) to increase supply chain efficiency.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The 1965 reforms somewhat altered the role of the Party in economic administration.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Local officials were to oversee operations from a distance to ensure compliance with the spirit of the reforms.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The plan called for more detailed and scientific central planning, including annual targets.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] These plans would be calculated using computer systems.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Distribution of supplies and products would take place in different ways.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Central planners would allocate certain scarce and vital goods.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] For others, enterprises could form "direct ties" within which they developed a contractual exchange relationship.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The authors of the reforms knew from the outset that changes would take effect gradually, based on the careful writing of plans through the years 1966 and 1967.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The first 43 enterprises, along with several "experiments" for which planning began before the September 1965 Plenum, shifted to the new model at the beginning of 1966.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Transfer of another 180–200 was accomplished in early 1966.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] These were already profitable, well-positioned businesses, and reflected well on the reform in early evaluations.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] On July 1, 1966, 430 more enterprises were transferred; these included some large operations and themselves constituted 12% of total production.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] By the end of 1966, more than 704 enterprises had switched.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The Eighth Five-Year Plan would have instantiated some of the proposed reforms.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] (The Five-Year Plan dealt with a broad range of issues, with more of a focus on people's overall living conditions.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Most light industry was to transfer at the beginning of 1967.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The remaining enterprises to switch over in two stages, taking effect on July 1, 1967, and January 1, 1968.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The complete transfer of all enterprises proceeded steadily, if not exactly on schedule.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] By April 1, 1967, 2,500 enterprises, responsible for 20% of output, had switched.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] By the end of the year, 7,000 industrial enterprises (out of 45,000), 1,500 trucking firms (out of 4,100), and all 25 railroad systems had transferred.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Together these made up the backbone of Soviet industry.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] They were followed by smaller enterprises: 11,000 more in 1968.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The plan met with considerable initial confusion from enterprise managers who, throughout their careers, had underestimated their potential output in order to later exceed their quota.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Also difficult was the requirement to comply with the new directives before all aspects of the economy (i.e., prices, resource availability) had shifted over.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] And the reluctance of certain bureaucrats to comply with the new policies was the subject of sustained criticism in the press, including multiple editorials by Liberman himself.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] In April 1966, for example, Liberman recommended creating a "brain trust of the reconstruction" which could veto counter-reformist policies in the bureaucracy.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Officials at the higher administrative levels (i.e., the ministries), continued to issue orders at odds with the profitability plans of the enterprise managers.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Some traditional problems—such as accumulation (which undercut profitability) of surplus valuable supplies, lest they be needed later in a time of shortage—persisted.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Gossnab and the ministries were blamed for failing to make the appropriate inputs available to the enterprises.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] A price revision, the first since 1955, was announced in mid-1966, apparently following some non-trivial internal disputes.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The revision called for moderate re-alignment of prices, to conform more with production costs, and went into effect in July 1967.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Wholesale fuel and ore prices increased substantially.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Prices on consumer goods did not officially increase at all; yet consumers paid higher prices for things they wanted and needed, since newer, more expensive goods were introduced to the market, and the old versions withdrawn.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Many enterprises were encouraged to sell or give away excess equipment, since all available capital was factored into the calculation of productivity.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Certain measurements of efficiency improved.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] These included rising sales per rouble worth of capital and falling wages per rouble of sales.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The enterprises rendered large portions of their profits, sometimes 80%, to the central budget.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] These payments of "free" remaining profits substantially exceeded capital charges.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] However, central planners were not satisfied with the impact of the reform.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] In particular, they observed that wages had increased without a commensurate rise in productivity.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Many of the specific changes were revised or reversed in 1969–1971.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The reforms somewhat reduced the role of the Party in micromanaging economic operations.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] The backlash against economic reformism joined with opposition to political liberalization to trigger the full-blown invasion of Czechoslovakia in 1968.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1965-soviet-economic-reform] Soviet officials and press nevertheless continued to advance the idea of the 1965 reform.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1968-red-square-demonstration] The **1968 Red Square demonstration** (Russian: Демонстра́ция 25 а́вгуста 1968 го́да) took place in Moscow on 25 August 1968.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1968-red-square-demonstration] It was a protest by eight demonstrators against the invasion of Czechoslovakia on the night of 20–21 August 1968 by the Soviet Union and its Warsaw Pact allies, crushing the Prague Spring, the challenge to centralised planning and censorship by communist leader Alexander Dubček.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1968-red-square-demonstration] The protest took place at the Lobnoye Mesto (Place of Proclamation) on Red Square next to the Kremlin, to avoid any accusation of a violation of public order.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1968-red-square-demonstration] It was a nonviolent, sit-down demonstration.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1968-red-square-demonstration] However, all but one of the protestors were quickly and roughly arrested by police and plainclothes KGB men.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1968-red-square-demonstration] Within a few minutes, seven of the protesters were assaulted, brutally beaten and loaded into cars by KGB operatives.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1968-red-square-demonstration] The Czechoslovak flag was broken, and the placards were confiscated.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1968-red-square-demonstration] Since Natalya Gorbanevskaya had recently given birth, she was not made to stand trial.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1968-red-square-demonstration] The other protesters convinced 21-year-old Tatiana Baeva to declare that she had been at the scene by accident, and she was released soon after.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1968-red-square-demonstration] The KGB failed to find out which protester was holding which banner; therefore, all the banners were attributed to each protester, except for Tatiana Baeva, who was released.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1968-red-square-demonstration] The banners were branded by the KGB as "anti-Soviet".
[src:alexei-kosygin/1968-red-square-demonstration] During the investigation and trial, the defence revealed several inconsistencies in the accusations.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1968-red-square-demonstration] One of the eyewitnesses declared that he saw protesters leaving the GUM, a large store in the vicinity, even though this store is closed on Sundays.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1968-red-square-demonstration] Additionally, all eyewitnesses happened to be from the same military division, even though they all claimed that they ended up on Red Square accidentally.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1968-red-square-demonstration] However, these inconsistencies were not taken into account during the trial.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1968-red-square-demonstration] None of the demonstrators pleaded guilty.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1968-red-square-demonstration] Vadim Delaunay and Vladimir Dremlyuga were sentenced to three years in a penal colony.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1968-red-square-demonstration] Victor Fainberg, who had his teeth knocked out during the arrest, did not appear in court but was sent to a psychiatric prison.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1968-red-square-demonstration] Larisa Bogoraz was sentenced to four years of exile to a remote Siberian settlement in the Irkutsk Region.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1968-red-square-demonstration] Konstantin Babitsky was sentenced to three years of exile.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1968-red-square-demonstration] Pavel Litvinov was sentenced to five years' exile.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1968-red-square-demonstration] Natalya Gorbanevskaya was released the same day but later sent to a psychiatric prison.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1968-red-square-demonstration] In his "Attorney's waltz" singer and rights activist Yuliy Kim claimed that the sentences had been decided before the trial.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1968-red-square-demonstration] In another song, "Ilyich", Kim mentions Yuri Andropov's and Leonid Brezhnev's anger at the demonstration, and refers to three of the protestors by name -- Pavel Litvinov, Natalya Gorbanevskaya and Larisa Bogoraz.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1968-red-square-demonstration] The story of the August 1968 demonstration is recounted in the 2005 documentary *They Chose Freedom*.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1968-red-square-demonstration] In 1990 (following the Velvet Revolution), seven of the protesters were awarded honorary citizenship of Prague.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1968-red-square-demonstration] During the conflict in South Ossetia, August 2008, the former president of the Czech Republic, Václav Havel, expressed his sympathies for the protesters of 1968.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1968-red-square-demonstration] Czech Premier Mirek Topolánek recognized the heroism of the protesters with awards.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1968-red-square-demonstration] There was no recognition on the part of the Russian government.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1968-red-square-demonstration] On 24 August 2008, the similar demonstration with the slogan For your freedom and ours was held in the same place.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1968-red-square-demonstration] On 25 August 2013, the 45th anniversary of the demonstration, Gorbanevskaya and several of her friends recreated the original protest, again featuring the "For your freedom and ours" banner.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1968-red-square-demonstration] Ten participants (among them Delaunay's son Sergey) were arrested almost immediately and taken to a police station.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1968-red-square-demonstration] They were soon arraigned and released pending court appearance on charges of failing to secure prior permission for a political rally, a misdemeanor under current Russian law.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1968-red-square-demonstration] In 2018, three participants at another repeat demonstration were arrested.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1968-red-square-demonstration] On February 5, 2025, Tatiana Baeva, who was one of the participant members of the 1968 Red Square demonstration died at the age of 77.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In an effort that was led by Faisal of Saudi Arabia, the initial countries that OAPEC targeted were Canada, Japan, the Netherlands, the United Kingdom, and the United States.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] This list was later expanded to include Portugal, Rhodesia, and South Africa.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In March 1974, OAPEC lifted the embargo, but the price of oil had risen by nearly 300%: from US$3 per barrel ($19/m3) to nearly US$12 per barrel ($75/m3) globally.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Prices in the United States were significantly higher than the global average.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After it was implemented, the embargo caused an oil crisis, or "shock", with many short- and long-term effects on the global economy as well as on global politics.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The 1973 embargo later came to be referred to as the **first oil shock**.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] A second oil shock occurred in 1979 in the aftermath of the Iranian Revolution.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Following the Israeli Declaration of Independence in 1948, there has been conflict between Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East, including several wars.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Suez Crisis, also known as the Second Arab–Israeli war, was sparked by Israel's southern port of Eilat being blocked by Egypt, which also nationalized the Suez Canal belonging to French and British investors.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] As a result of the war, the Suez Canal was closed for several months between 1956 and 1957.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Six-Day War of 1967 included an Israeli invasion of the Egyptian Sinai Peninsula, which resulted in Egypt closing the Suez Canal for eight years.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Following the Yom Kippur War, the canal was cleared in 1974 and opened again in 1975.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OAPEC countries cut production of oil and placed an embargo on oil exports to the United States after Richard Nixon requested $2.2 billion to support Israel's war effort.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nevertheless, the embargo lasted only until January 1974, though the price of oil remained high afterwards.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] By 1969, American domestic production of oil was peaking and could not keep pace with increasing demand from vehicles.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The US was importing 350 million barrels (56 million cubic metres) per year by the late 1950s, mostly from Venezuela and Canada.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Because of transportation costs and tariffs, it never purchased much oil from the Middle East.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1973, US production had declined to 16% of global output.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Eisenhower imposed quotas on foreign oil that would stay in place between 1959 and 1973.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Critics called it the "drain America first" policy.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Some scholars believe the policy contributed to the decline of domestic US oil production in the early 1970s.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The cheapness of oil compared with coal led to the decline of the coal industry.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1951, 51% of the United States' energy came from coal, and by 1973, only 19% of American industry was coal-based.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The decline in domestic oil production, combined with the country's increasing reliance on oil as a source of power, made the US economy vulnerable to a foreign oil embargo.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] When Richard Nixon became US president in 1969, he assigned George Shultz to head a committee to review the Eisenhower-era quota program.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Shultz's committee recommended that the quotas be abolished and replaced with tariffs, but Nixon decided to keep the quotas due to vigorous political opposition.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon imposed a price ceiling on oil in August 1971 as demand for oil was increasing and production was declining, which increased dependence on oil imports as consumption was bolstered by low prices.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1973, Nixon announced the end of the quota system.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Between 1970 and 1973 US imports of crude oil had nearly doubled, reaching 6.2 million barrels per day in 1973.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Until 1973, an abundance of oil supply had kept the market price of oil lower than the posted price.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1970, American oil production peaked and the United States began to import more oil.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Oil imports rose by 52% between 1969 and 1972.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] By 1972, 83% of the American oil imports came from the Middle East.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Throughout the 1960s, the price for a barrel of oil remained at $1.80, meaning that with the effects of inflation considered the price of oil in real terms got progressively lower throughout the decade, with Americans paying less for oil in 1969 than they had in 1959.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Even after a price for a barrel of oil rose to $2.00 in 1971, adjusted for inflation, people in the Western nations were paying less for oil in 1971 than they had in 1958.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The extremely low price of oil served as the basis for the "long summer" of prosperity and mass affluence that began in 1945.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC), was founded by five oil producing countries at a Baghdad conference on 14 September 1960.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The five founding members of OPEC were Venezuela, Iraq, Saudi Arabia, Iran and Kuwait.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OPEC was organized after the oil companies slashed the posted price of oil, but the posted price of oil remained consistently higher than the market price of oil between 1961 and 1972.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1963, the Seven Sisters controlled 86% of the oil produced by OPEC countries, but by 1970 the rise of "independent oil companies" had decreased their share to 77%.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The entry of three new oil producers—Algeria, Libya and Nigeria—meant that by 1970, 81 oil companies were doing business in the Middle East.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In the early 1960s Libya, Indonesia and Qatar joined OPEC.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OPEC was generally regarded as ineffective until political turbulence in Libya and Iraq strengthened their position in 1970.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Additionally, increasing Soviet influence provided oil producing countries with alternative means of transporting oil to markets.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Under the Tehran Price Agreement of 1971, signed on 14 February, the posted price of oil was increased and, due to a decline in the value of the US dollar relative to gold, certain anti-inflationary measures were enacted.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] A severe drain on US gold reserves lead to higher inflation and lack of confidence in the strength of the dollar, President Nixon issued Executive Order 11615 on August 15, 1971, which closed the gold window.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] This action made the dollar inconvertible to gold directly, except on the open market, and was soon dubbed the *Nixon Shock*, leading eventually to the collapse of the Bretton Woods system in 1976.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Because oil was priced in dollars, oil producers' real income decreased when the dollar started to float free of the old link to gold.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In September 1971, OPEC issued a joint communiqué stating that from then on, they would price oil in terms of a fixed amount of gold.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After 1971, OPEC was slow to readjust prices to reflect this depreciation.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] From 1947 to 1967, the dollar price of oil had risen by less than two percent per year.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Until the oil shock, the price had also remained fairly stable versus other currencies and commodities.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OPEC ministers had not developed institutional mechanisms to update prices in sync with changing market conditions, so their real incomes lagged.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The substantial price increases of 1973–1974 largely returned their prices and corresponding incomes to former levels in terms of commodities such as gold.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Arab oil producing countries had attempted to use oil as leverage to influence political events on two prior occasions—the first was the Suez Crisis in 1956 when the United Kingdom, France and Israel invaded Egypt.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] During the conflict the Syrians sabotaged both the Trans-Arabian Pipeline and the Iraq–Baniyas pipeline, which disrupted the supply of oil to Western Europe.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The second instance was when war broke out between Egypt and Israel in 1967, but despite continued Egyptian and Syrian enmity against Israel, the embargo lasted only a few months.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Most scholars agree that the 1967 embargo was ineffective.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Although some members of the Organization of Arab Petroleum Exporting Countries (OAPEC) supported the use of oil as a weapon to influence the political outcome of the Arab–Israeli conflict, Saudi Arabia had traditionally been the strongest supporter of separating oil from politics.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Saudis were wary of the tactic due to the availability of oil from non-Arab oil producing countries, and in the decades leading up to the crisis, the region's conservative monarchies had grown dependent on Western support to ensure their continued survival as Nasserism gained traction.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On the other hand, Algeria, Iraq and Libya had strongly supported the use of oil as a weapon in the conflict.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Arab newspapers like the Egyptian *Al-Ahram*, Lebanese *An-Nahar* and Iraqi *Al-Thawra* had historically been supportive of the use of oil as a weapon.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1970, President Nasser of Egypt died and was succeeded by Anwar Sadat, a man who believed in the diplomacy of surprise, in engaging in sudden moves to upset the diplomatic equilibrium.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Sadat liked to say that his favourite game was backgammon, a game where skill and persistence was rewarded, but was best won by sudden gambles, making an analogy between how he played backgammon and conducted his diplomacy.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Under Nasser, Egypt and Saudi Arabia had engaged what was known as the Arab Cold War, but Sadat got along very well with King Faisal of Saudi Arabia, forming an alliance between the most populous Arab state and the wealthiest Arab state.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Unlike the secularist Nasser, Sadat was a pious Muslim and he had a strong personal rapport with King Faisal, who was an equally pious Muslim.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The man largely in charge of American foreign policy, the National Security Adviser, Henry Kissinger, later admitted that he was so engrossed with the Paris peace talks to end the Vietnam war that he and others in Washington missed the significance of the Egyptian-Saudi alliance.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At the same time that Sadat moved closer to Saudi Arabia, he also wanted a rapprochement with the United States and to move Egypt away from its alliance with the Soviet Union.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In 1971, the US had information that the Arab states were willing to implement another embargo.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In July 1972, Sadat expelled all 16,000 of the Soviet military personnel in Egypt in a signal that he wanted better relations with the United States.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger was taken completely by surprise by Sadat's move, saying: "Why has he done me this favor?
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] For Sadat, cost was no object as the money to buy Soviet arms came from Saudi Arabia.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At the same time, Faisal promised Sadat that if it should come to war, Saudi Arabia would embargo oil to the West.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In April 1973, the Saudi Oil Minister Ahmed Zaki Yamani visited Washington to meet Kissinger and told him that King Faisal was becoming more and more unhappy with the United States, saying he wanted America to pressure Israel to return all the lands captured in the Six Day War of 1967.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In a later interview, Yamani accused Kissinger of not taking his warning seriously, saying all he did was to ask him not to speak anymore of this threat.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Angry at Kissinger, Yamani, in an interview with the *Washington Post* on April 19, 1973, warned that King Faisal was considering an oil embargo.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At the time, the general feeling in Washington was the Saudis were bluffing and nothing would come of their threat to impose an oil embargo.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The fact that Faisal's ineffectual half brother King Saud had imposed a crippling oil embargo on Britain and France during the Suez War of 1956 was not considered an important precedent.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The CEOs of four of the United States' oil companies, after speaking with Faisal, arrived in Washington in May 1973 with the warning that Faisal was considerably tougher, more intelligent and more ruthless than his half-brother Saud whom he had deposed in 1964, and that his threats were serious.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger declined to meet the four CEOs.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In an assessment done by Kissinger and his staff about the Middle East in the summer of 1973, the repeated statements by Sadat about waging *jihad* against Israel were dismissed as empty talk, while the warnings from King Faisal were likewise regarded as inconsequential.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In September 1973, Nixon fired Rogers as Secretary of State and replaced him with Kissinger.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger later stated he had not been given enough time to know the Middle East, as he settled into the State Department's office at Foggy Bottom as Egypt and Syria attacked Israel on 6 October 1973.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 6 October 1973, the Yom Kippur began when Egypt attacked the Bar Lev Line in the Sinai Peninsula and Syria launched an offensive in the Golan Heights, both of which had been occupied by Israel during the 1967 Six-Day War.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal of Saudi Arabia was supportive, and on 8 October 1973, he told two Egyptian envoys: "You have made us all proud.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In the past we could not lift our heads up.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] He promised to give to Egypt a quality of aid worth $200 million US dollars to assist with the war effort, and stated he was willing to use the "oil weapon" if necessary to support Egypt.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The war began during the height of the Watergate scandal; as such Nixon largely let Kissinger manage foreign policy as he, Nixon, was distracted by the scandal.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger promised Israeli Prime Minister Golda Meir that the United States would replace its losses in equipment after the war.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon had ordered an arms lift to Israel on 12 October 1973, but Kissinger used the excuse of bureaucratic delays to limit the amount of weapons and ammunition sent to Israel.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Arab concept of the "peace of the brave", i.e. a victorious leader being magnanimous to his defeated opponents, meant there was a possibility that Sadat at least would make peace with Israel provided that the war ended in such a way that Egypt was not perceived to be defeated.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Likewise, Kissinger regarded Meir as being rather arrogant and believed that an armistice that ended the war in a manner that was not an unambiguous Israeli victory would make her more humble.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] As both Syria and Egypt lost much equipment during the fighting, the Soviet Union began to fly new equipment in, starting on 12 October.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Soviet flights to Syria and Egypt were recorded by the British radar stations in Cyprus.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Though the Soviets were flying in an average of 60 flights per day, exaggerated accounts appeared in Western newspapers speaking of "one hundred flights per day".
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At this point, both Nixon and Kissinger began to see the October War more in terms of the Cold War rather than Middle Eastern politics, both seeing the Soviet arms lifts to Egypt and Syria as a Soviet power play that required an American answer.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On October 12, 1973, US president Richard Nixon authorized Operation Nickel Grass, a strategic airlift to deliver weapons and supplies to Israel in order to replace its materiel losses.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The first American weapons to Israel arrived on 15 October 1973, and despite Nixon's orders the number of American planes flying into Tel Aviv were initially limited.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After the first week of the war, the Israelis had halted the Syrian offensive in the Golan Heights and were pushing back the Syrians back towards Damascus.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Along the Suez canal, however, there was heavy fighting, with the Egyptians holding their own.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] At an OPEC summit at the Sheraton Hotel in Kuwait City on 16 October 1973, it was announced the price of oil would go from $3.01 US dollars per barrel to $5.12 per barrel.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The news about the war on 16 October was grim from the Arab viewpoint, with the Syrians steadily being pushed back, while Israelis had opened a counter-offensive against the Egyptians and crossed the Great Bitter Lake.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Responses from stated representatives at the meeting were varied.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Saudi Oil Minister Ahmed Zaki Yamani stated, in a 1981 interview, that "[t]he king still wanted to give America a chance to stay out of the fighting.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] So we agreed to cut back production by just 5 percent per month.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] A full embargo, we agreed, was something we would implement only if we felt that things were absolutely hopeless".
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Iranian delegation left the summit after agreeing to the price increase, as the Shah of Iran only supported higher oil prices.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Oil Minister of Iraq, Sa'dun Hammadi demanded the "total nationalization" of all assets of American oil companies in the Middle East, the withdrawal of all Arab funds from the United States and for all Arab states to break diplomatic relations with the United States.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Libyan Oil Minister, Izz al-Din al-Mabruk, called for the nationalization of all the assets of all Western oil companies in the Middle East.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The Saudi delegation led by Yemani, supported by the Algerian delegation, fought hard against the Iraqi and Libyan demands for an embargo, as Yemani maintained that forcing through an increase in the price of oil was the best way to influence the United States.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Hammadi and the rest of the Iraqi delegation left upset as Yemani had won over the majority of the delegations to the Saudi viewpoint.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The statement issued after midnight at the Sheraton Hotel was handwritten and, reflecting the tense talk, had several paragraphs crossed out while other paragraphs were written in by different hands.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 17 October, Arab oil producers cut production by 5% and threatened an oil embargo against Israel's wartime allies: the United States, the Netherlands, Rhodesia, South Africa, and Portugal.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 17–19 October 1973, the Saudi Foreign Minister, Omar Al Saqqaf, visited Washington together with the foreign ministers of Algeria, Kuwait and Morocco to warn that there was a real possibility of an oil embargo being imposed.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon promised him that the United States would mediate a settlement to the war that would be "peaceful, just and honorable" to both sides.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] He had ended the Vietnam war on what he felt was an honorable basis and now intended to end the October war in the same manner.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Saqqaf complained to King Faisal that Nixon seemed more interested in a dispute about "a burglary" (i.e. the Watergate scandal) than about the war.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] During a press conference, an American reporter mocked the threat of an embargo, contemptuously saying the Saudis "could drink their oil", leading Saqqaf to reply in anger "All right, we will!".
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Israel took heavy losses in men and materiel during the fighting against Egypt and Syria, and on 18 October 1973, Meir requested $850 million worth of American arms and equipment to replace its materiel losses.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon decided, characteristically, to act on an epic scale; Instead of the $850 million worth of arms requested, he sent a request to Congress for some $2.2 billion worth of arms to Israel, which was promptly approved.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Nixon, whose administration was being badly battered by the Watergate scandal, felt that a bold foreign policy move might resuscitate his administration.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In an interview with the British historian Robert Lacey in 1981, Kissinger later admitted about the arms lift to Israel: "I made a mistake.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In retrospect it was not the best considered decision we made".
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The arms lift enraged King Faisal of Saudi Arabia.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal was angry that Israel had only asked for $850 million worth of American weapons, and instead received an unsolicited $2.2 billion worth of weapons, which he perceived as a sign of the pro-Israeli slant of American foreign policy.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal also felt insulted that Nixon had just promised Saqqaf an "honorable" peace the day before he submitted the request to Congress for some $2.2 billion worth of arms for Israel, which he saw as an act of duplicity on Nixon's part.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal had been opposed to a total embargo and only agreed to the 5% cut on 17 October under pressure from other Arab states.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal felt his efforts on behalf the United States were not being appreciated in Washington, which increased his fury at Nixon.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On the afternoon of 19 October 1973, Faisal was in his office when he learned about the United States sending $2.2 billion worth of weapons to Israel, and discussed the issue with two of his closest advisers, Abdullah ibn Abdul Rahman and Rashad Pharaon.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The king called Yamani at about 8 pm, and told him he was needed at the Riyassa Palace immediately.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Yamani told the king: "The TV news goes out at nine.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] If you make a decision now, we can get it announced at once".
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The king replied "Write this down" and announced he was placing a total embargo on the United States.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Most of the other oil-producing Arab states joined the embargo.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Algeria, Iraq, and Libya promoted the embargo, but did not actively enforce it.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo was accompanied by gradual monthly production cuts—by December, production had been cut to 25% of September levels.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] This contributed to a global recession and increased tension between the United States and several of its European allies, who faulted the US for provoking an embargo by providing what many viewed as unconditional assistance to Israel.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] OAPEC demanded a complete Israeli withdrawal from all territories beyond the 1949 Armistice border.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo lasted from October 1973 to March 1974.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Because every Arab state except for Iraq and Libya joined the oil embargo, oil exports from the Middle East to the West were down by 60–70% by November 1973.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Japan and the nations of western Europe imported some 75% of their oil from the Near East.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo led to immediate and sharp price raises, as Lacey noted that "competing desperately for dwindling supplies, consumers showed themselves willing to pay unparalleled money for their oil".
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Saudi Arabia had 25% of the world's oil reserves.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The embargo imposed on the United States led to shortages of oil in the United States, which set an inflationary spiral, as the new high prices for oil in the American market led to sharp increases of the price of oil in nations not subjected to the embargo.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] When the Iranian state oil company held an auction on 16 December 1973, bids for some $17 US dollars per barrel of oil were made.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] In late December 1973, OPEC held a conference in Vienna when it was announced the price for a barrel of oil was to increase from $5 US dollars per barrel to $11.65 US dollars per barrel.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal was opposed to the price increase, which was largely the work of the Iranian delegation.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 22 February 1974, King Faisal chaired the second summit of Islamic states in Lahore, which, unlike the first summit that Faisal had chaired in 1969, was not boycotted by Iraq and Syria.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Faisal was acclaimed as a conquering hero who humiliated and humbled the West by wrecking its economy.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] The prime minister of Pakistan, Zulfikar Ali Bhutto, opened the conference by stating: "The armies of Pakistan are the armies of Islam.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On November 7, 1973, Kissinger flew to Riyadh to meet King Faisal and ask him to end the oil embargo in exchange for promising to be "evenhanded" with the Arab-Israeli dispute.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] As the plane carrying him prepared to land in Riyadh, Kissinger was clearly nervous at the prospect of negotiating with the stern Wahhabi Faisal who had a marked dislike of Jews.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] During a summit in Cairo the day before, Kissinger asked Sadat what Faisal was like and was told: "Well, Dr.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Henry, he will probably go on with you about Communism and the Jews".
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] King Faisal's two great hatreds were communism and Zionism, as he believed that the Soviet Union and Israel were plotting together against Islam.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Initially, Secretary of Defense James Schlesinger suggested to Kissinger that the USA invade Saudi Arabia and another Arab countries and seize their oil fields.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger stated in a private state department meeting that it's “ridiculous that the civilized world is held up by 8 million savages...
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Can’t we overthrow one of the sheikhs just to show that we can do it?” They formed a plan to invade Abu Dhabi, Kuwait, and Saudi Arabia.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Kissinger publicly threatened "countermeasures" in a November 21, 1973 press conference if the embargo was not lifted, and the Saudis responded with threatening further oil cuts and to burn their oil fields if the US military invaded.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] After the CIA confirmed these threats, Kissinger gave up military intervention and decided to deal with Israel's troop withdrawals, settling on diplomatic solutions to the oil embargo.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] On 18 March 1974, King Faisal ended the oil embargo.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Sadat had reported to Faisal that the United States was being more "evenhanded", and Kissinger had promised to sell Saudi Arabia weapons that it had previously denied under the grounds that they might be used against Israel.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Since Israeli forces did not withdraw to the 1949 Armistice Line, the majority of scholars believe that the embargo was a failure.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Roy Licklieder, in his 1988 book *Political Power and the Arab Oil Weapon*, concluded that the embargo was a failure because the countries that were targeted by the embargo did not change their policies on the Arab–Israeli conflict.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Licklieder believed that any long term changes were caused by the OPEC increase in the posted price of oil, and not the OAPEC embargo.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Daniel Yergin, on the other hand, has said that the embargo "remade the international economy".
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] Over the long term, the oil embargo changed the nature of policy in the West towards increased exploration, alternative energy research, energy conservation and more restrictive monetary policy to better fight inflation.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p01] For further details see the "Energy crisis" series by Facts on File.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The effects of the embargo were immediate.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] OPEC forced oil companies to increase payments drastically.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The price of oil quadrupled by 1974 from US$3 to nearly US$12 per 42 gallon barrel ($75 per cubic meter), equivalent in 2018 dollars to a price rise from $17 to $61 per barrel.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Saudi Arabia had 25% of the world's oil, but only 4% of the oil used in the United States in 1973 came from the kingdom.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] However, Saudi Arabia plays an over-sized role within the Arab world.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1973, about 25% of the oil used in the United States came from Arab countries.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The shortage of oil within the United States caused by the Arab oil embargo forced prices to rise, which led price rises globally.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Oil producers that had not joined the embargo such as Iran, Venezuela, Libya and Iraq demanded higher prices in Japan and Europe, as an initiative to ship oil to those places instead of the United States, setting off a worldwide inflationary spiral.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Although the embargo did not severely disrupt US oil supplies—since Americans imported more oil from non-embargoed nations such as Iran—the resulting 400% increase in oil prices caused by the embargo damaged the American economy.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A number of nations such as Venezuela, Nigeria, Iran and Iraq increased their oil production during the embargo, and sold their oil at a higher price.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The leader who pushed the most for higher oil prices was the Shah of Iran, and the Italian historian Giuliano Garavini has argued that the leader most responsible for the West's economic problems during the "oil shock" was not King Faisal, but rather the Shah.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Some of the nations that were classified as "friendly" to the Arab viewpoint in regards to the Arab-Israeli dispute such as France and Belgium were the ones who suffered the most from the worldwide inflation caused by the embargo.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In March 1974, the crisis eased when the embargo was lifted after negotiations at the Washington Oil Summit, but the effects lingered throughout the 1970s.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The dollar price of energy increased again in 1975, amid the weakening competitive position of the dollar in world markets.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Arab oil embargo ended the long period of prosperity in the West that had begun in 1945, throwing the world's economy into the steepest economic contraction since the Great Depression.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The "long summer" of prosperity in the post-war years had made possible the "swinging sixties" and the related rise of a rebellious youth culture, as it was easy to be hedonist or in rebellion against traditional values in a time of unprecedented prosperity.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] 1945 to 1973 had been a period of unprecedented prosperity in the West, a "long summer" that many believed would never end.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Its abrupt end in 1973, as the oil embargo increased the price of oil by 400% within a matter of days and threw the world's economy into a sharp recession, with unemployment mounting and inflation raging, came as a profound shock.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The end of what the French called the *Trente Glorieuses* ("Glorious Thirty" [years]) led to widespread pessimism in the West, with the *Financial Times* running a famous headline in late 1973 saying, "The Future will be subject to Delay".
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In an August 1974 address to the General Assembly, Kurt Waldheim, the secretary-general of the United Nations, complained about "the note of helplessness and fatalism creeping into world affairs".
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The sudden and abrupt end of the "long summer" of prosperity in 1973-1974 played a major role in the pessimistic mood that characterized the culture of the West of the 1970s.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1975, a report to Congress from the Federal Energy Administration estimated that the embargo of 1973–1974 had caused about 500,000 Americans to lose their jobs, and caused a GNP loss between $10 billion–$20 billion.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] This price increase had a dramatic effect on oil exporting nations, for the countries of the Middle East who had long been dominated by the industrial powers were seen to have taken control of a vital commodity.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil-exporting nations began to accumulate vast wealth.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Some of the income was dispensed in the form of aid to other underdeveloped nations whose economies had been caught between higher oil prices and lower prices for their own export commodities, amid shrinking Western demand.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Much went for arms purchases that exacerbated political tensions, particularly in the Middle East.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The 400% increase in the world oil prices led to extravagant promises being made by the leaders of oil-producing nations.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Shah of Iran told his subjects in a speech in December 1973 that he was launching "Great Civilization" project that would make Iran into a First World nation by the 1990s.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] President Carlos Andrés Pérez of Venezuela likewise launched his *Le Gran Venezuela* project intended to make Venezuela into a First World nation.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] President Yakubu Gowon of Nigeria told his people that henceforward Nigeria's main problem would be "managing abundance".
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] After the oil shock, Nigeria presented itself as the first African nation that would reach First World status.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In Lagos, a series of stately modernist buildings were erected as appropriate for a nation that saw itself as the leader of all Black Africa.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Much of the oil wealth in Nigeria was stolen by corrupt politicians.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] At least some of Nigeria's new oil wealth went to rebuild the areas devastated by the civil war of 1967-1970 and to address the complaints that too much of Nigeria's oil wealth went to the federal government in Lagos instead of the people.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The new wealth generated by the "oil shock" allowed for Chairman Houari Boumédiène of Algeria to become a global leader, courted by elites in the First World and the Third World.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil embargo led a sudden interest in the Palestinian issue.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Between 1973 and 1981, Saudi Arabia donated a sum worth $1 billion US dollars to the Palestine Liberation Organization, which thus had a budget that exceeded that of many Third World nations.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On November 8, 1973, Kissinger became the first Secretary of State to meet with a Saudi leader since 1953, as he met King Faisal to ask him to end the embargo.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Within two week of the embargo being launched, all of the foreign ministers of the nations of the European Economic Community, now the European Union, met in a conference to issue a statement calling for Israel "to end the territorial occupation which has maintained since the conflict of 1967".
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On December 11, 1973, the Japanese Foreign Minister Masayoshi Ōhira flew in to Riyadh to meet King Faisal for "talks on improving bilateral relations".
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Shortly afterwards, the French foreign minister Michel Jobert arrived to sign an agreement that provided oil for France for the next twenty years.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On January 24, 1974, as the Shah of Iran, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, was coming off the ski slopes of St.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Moritz, he was met by the British Chancellor of Exchequer, Anthony Barber, and the Trade Secretary, Peter Walker.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In a role-reversal, Barber and Walker paid homage to the Shah, who promised them that his nation would sell the United Kingdom 5 million tons of oil in exchange for some £100 million of British goods, to aid his plans to industrialize Iran.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Saudi Arabia experienced an upsurge of prosperity and affluence after the oil embargo, whose consequences horrified King Faisal.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Faisal, who was devoted to a harsh puritanical strain of Sunni Islam known in the West as Wahhabism, was appalled by the way that his subjects became materialistic, devoted only to conspicuous consumption and greed as they lost interest in Islam.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Lacey wrote: "The spiritual dangers of easy affluence distressed him more.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] His simple gesture of piety and honor seemed to have opened a Pandora's Box that threatened to turn his realm into a parody of all he held dear".
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the last two of years of his life, Faisal fell into depression over the way his subjects had been seduced into a consumerist lifestyle, becoming lost in a sense of "melancholia".
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Faisal's son, Crown Prince Mohammad told Lacey in 1981: "The profligacy, the greed, he felt he could not stem it.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] He become so bound up in his work, there was almost nothing private of him left".
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A sign of the changed values was that despite the total ban on alcohol in Saudi Arabia, drinking and drug use became common with the younger members of the House of Saud.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] James Akins, the American ambassador in Riyadh reported; "the sky over Riyadh is black with vultures with new get-richer-quicker plans under their wings".
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1974, property prices in Riyadh doubled on a weekly basis for the entire year, as the prosperity led to a real estate speculation bubble that was often compared to the Klondike gold rush of 1898–1899.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] At the Red Sea port of Jeddah, there were so many ships queuing up laden with cement for the construction boom in Saudi Arabia, that construction contractors hired helicopters to fly the cement in, twenty bags per flight.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A number of families engaged in the Saudi construction industry such as the Juffali, Alireza, al-Khasshoggi and the bin Laden families all became very wealthy as a result of the construction boom.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The period after the oil shock of 1973–1974 is still fondly remembered in Saudi Arabia as the "age of abundance", where nearly everyone had a significant increase in their standard of living.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The wealth and corruption generated by the oil shock led to a fundamentalist backlash in Saudi Arabia.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On 20 November 1979, Islam's holiest shrine, the Grand Mosque of Mecca, was seized by a group who proclaimed themselves to be the followers of the Mahdi, a messianic figure said to appear at the dawn of every Muslim century to strike down the enemies of Islam.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The leader of the uprising, Juhayman al-Otaybi, read out a list of grievances, as he accused the House of Saud of being corrupt and degenerate, listing by name a number of Saudi princes who were engaged in dubious business dealings and/or who drank alcohol.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Saudi Army recaptured the Grand Mosque, and the surviving "renegades", as the rebels were labelled, were executed.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In Algeria, the "oil shock" led to the establishment of a welfare state where none had existed previously.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The lower oil prices of the 1980s along with cutbacks and the belief that the FLN regime was corrupt helped cause the riots of October 1988 against the FLN regime, that killed at least 500 people.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The riots were largely caused by the fact that the low oil prices had forced the Algerian state to end many of its more generous social policies between 1986 and 1988, leading to an unemployment rate of 30% by 1988, along with the knowledge that the FLN regime had stolen millions.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the aftermath of the October riots, President Chadli Bendjedid began a transition to democracy.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The first free elections in Algeria in January 1992 were won by the Islamist FIS, which led to a military coup and an outbreak of a civil war that killed hundreds of thousands of Algerians.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] OPEC-member states raised the prospect of nationalization of oil company holdings.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Most notably, Saudi Arabia nationalized Aramco in 1980 under the leadership of Saudi oil minister Ahmed Zaki Yamani.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] As other OPEC nations followed suit, the cartel's income soared.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Saudi Arabia undertook a series of ambitious five-year development plans.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The biggest began in 1980, funded at $250 billion.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Other cartel members also undertook major economic development programs.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Control of oil became known as the "oil weapon".
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It came in the form of an embargo and production cutbacks from the Arab states.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The weapon was aimed at the United States, Great Britain, Canada, Japan and the Netherlands.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] These target governments perceived that the intent was to push them towards a more pro-Arab position.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] However, the affected countries did not undertake dramatic policy changes.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The risk that the Middle East could become another superpower confrontation with the USSR was of more concern to Washington than oil.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Further, interest groups and government agencies more worried about energy were no match for Kissinger's dominance.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The embargo had a negative influence on the US economy, causing immediate demands to address the threats to US energy security.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On an international level, the price increases changed competitive positions in many industries, such as automobiles.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Macroeconomic problems consisted of both inflationary and deflationary impacts.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The embargo left oil companies searching for new ways to increase oil supplies, even in rugged terrain such as the Arctic.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Finding oil and developing new fields usually required five to 10 years before significant production.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The average US retail price of a gallon of regular gasoline rose 43% from 38.5¢ in May 1973 to 55.1¢ in June 1974.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] State governments asked citizens not to put up Christmas lights.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Oregon banned Christmas and commercial lighting altogether.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Politicians called for a national gasoline rationing program.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Nixon asked gasoline retailers to voluntarily not sell gasoline on Saturday nights or Sundays.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] 90% of gas station owners complied, which produced long lines of motorists wanting to fill up their cars while they still could.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The "oil shock" provided considerable impetus to the American nuclear industry as a way to achieve "energy independence" from the Middle East.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On 7 November 1973, Nixon in an address to Congress called for Project Independence to make the United States self-sufficient in energy by 1980, which called for a massive investment in the nuclear industry.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Nixon envisioned nuclear energy as more economical, and was encouraged by the enthusiasm of many officials who saw nuclear energy as the technology of the future.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By the late 1960s, a lively environmentalist movement had emerged in the United States, and the Project Independence nuclear program was the subject of much debate in both the media and Congress.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The ensuing debates revealed that many of the claims made for nuclear power underestimated the true costs of nuclear reactors.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Equally problematic was where to safety store the spent nuclear rods that emitted a toxic level of radioactivity for centuries afterward, in a cost-effective manner.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The issue of the spent nuclear rods was especially difficult because of NIMBYism, where communities proved unwilling to accept a storage place for the inevitable by-product of nuclear power, the spent nuclear rods, with the demand that the government find some other community to store the rods.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Many of the nuclear reactors ordered in 1973 were cancelled due to cost overruns, while over 100 nuclear plants were shut down as uneconomical over the next 10 years.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Unlike nations that tried to use nuclear power as a way for energy independence such as France and Sweden, the United States had substantial reserves of its own oil, which weakened the case for nuclear power in the ensuring debates.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By 1989, only 18% of American energy came from nuclear power plants, which was a fraction of what Project Independence had envisioned in 1973.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil shock led to anti-Arab feelings becoming common.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Cartoons published in American newspapers during the oil shock depicted Arabs as disgusting, ugly, obese, corrupt and greedy.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the cartoons, the long hooked Semitic noses that had traditionally been featured in anti-Jewish cartoons were applied to the Arab sheiks as a way to illustrate their supposed greed.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] American public opinion did not see the use of the "oil weapon" as due to politics, and tended to explain the embargo as only due to the excessive greed of King Faisal and the other Arab leaders, hence the use of the hooked Semitic nose in the cartoons as a sort of shorthand for insatiable greed.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Soviet Union was not a beneficiary of the oil crisis.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The crisis prompted the USSR to raise energy prices within the Council on Mutual Economic Assistance (CMEA).
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The embargo was not uniform across Western Europe.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Of the nine members of the European Economic Community (EEC), the Netherlands faced a complete embargo.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By contrast Britain and France received almost uninterrupted supplies.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] That was their reward for refusing to allow the US to use their airfields and stopping arms and supplies to both the Arabs and the Israelis.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The other six EEC nations faced partial cutbacks.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The UK had traditionally been an ally of Israel, and Harold Wilson's government supported the Israelis during the Six-Day War.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] His successor, Ted Heath, reversed this policy in 1970, calling for Israel to withdraw to its pre-1967 borders.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The devalued franc made imports more expensive for French consumers, which encouraged them to buy French products, while making French products cheaper abroad.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] France was entirely dependent upon imported oil, through French companies continued to lease the oil concessions in Algeria until 1971.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The low price of oil internationally compensated to a certain extent for the higher price of oil caused by the devaluation.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The devalued franc ensured that the dramatic price increases caused by the oil shock hit the French economy especially hard in 1973.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The UK, Germany, Italy, Switzerland and Norway banned flying, driving and boating on Sundays.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Sweden rationed gasoline and heating oil.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Netherlands imposed prison sentences for those who used more than their ration of electricity.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The EEC was unable to achieve a common policy during the first month of the embargo.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It issued a statement on November 6, after the embargo and price rises had begun.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It was widely viewed as pro-Arab, supporting the Franco-British line on the war.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] OPEC duly lifted its embargo from all EEC members.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The other European states did not rally in defense of the Dutch who were left to fend for themselves and instead reached bilateral deals with Saudi Arabia, Iraq and Iran.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Faced with a recession, there was a tendency within the EEC nations to turn inwards away from European integration.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The price rises had a much greater impact in Europe than the embargo.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The crisis retarded the movement towards European economic integration which had been gathering pace ever since the EEC, now the European Union, had been founded in 1957.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In 1973, the German historian Jens-Uwe Wunderlich wrote that attempts to finish off the European common market came to a "complete standstill" in 1973 and it was not until 1977 that movement towards creating the common market resumed.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In particular, the oil shock increased the appeal of nuclear energy as a way to achieve energy independence from the turbulent Middle East.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Starting in March 1974 with the "Energy Plan" introduced by the premier Pierre Messmer, the French state made a massive investment in nuclear energy.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By the 1990s, 80% of all of France's energy came from nuclear plants.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The North Sea oil fields, which were discovered in 1969, did not start to be exploited until 1975, making the United Kingdom entirely dependent upon imported oil in 1973.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The way that world oil prices quadrupled in late 1973 had a very adverse impact on the British economy,.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In a series of speeches in December 1973, the Prime Minister Edward Heath warned that because of the oil shock that the British economy was going into recession and the British people should expect economic austerity.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Heath offered the coal miners a 7% wage increase, which was rejected as insufficient by the miners who went on strike.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Through not subjected to the embargo, the UK faced an energy crisis of its own—a series of strikes by coal miners and railroad workers over the winter of 1973–74 became a major factor in the defeat of Heath's Conservative government in the February 1974 general elections.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The new Labour government told the British to heat only one room in their houses over the winter.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Labour government of Harold Wilson settled the strike by giving the coal miners a 35% pay increase.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Japan was hard hit, since it imported 90% of its oil from the Middle East.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] It had a stockpile good for 55 days, and another 20-day supply was en route.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Facing its most serious crisis since 1945, the government ordered a 10% cut in the consumption of industrial oil and electricity.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In December 1973, it ordered an immediate 20% cut in oil use and electric power to Japan's major industries, and cutbacks in leisure automobile usage.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Economist predicted the growth rate would plunge from 5% annually, down to zero or even negative territory.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Seeking to take advantage of the crisis, Japanese business called on the government to relax its controls on air pollution and water pollution.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Moscow tried to take advantage by promising energy assistance if Japan renounced its claim to the Kurile Islands.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Instead it made $3.3 billion of dollars in loans to the Arab states and called on Israel to step back.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Japan's defensive strategy was explained to Kissinger when he met with top leaders in Tokyo in November 1973.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In the long run Japan never wavered in its determination to maintain very strong close ties to the United States, while in self-defense briefly providing the Arab powers with the rhetoric they demanded in return for resuming oil shipments in early 1974.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] To assure future oil flows, Japan added suppliers outside of the Middle East, invested in nuclear power, imposed conservation measures, and provided funding for Arab governments and the Palestinians.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The crisis was a major factor in the long-run shift of Japan's economy away from oil-intensive industries.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Japanese auto makers benefited from the crisis.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The jump in gasoline prices helped their small, fuel-efficient models to gain market share from the "gas-guzzling" Detroit competition.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] This triggered a drop in US sales of American cars that lasted into the 1980s.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil crisis contributed to the poor state of the Indian economy and played a role in Indira Gandhi's decision to impose The Emergency, a dictatorship.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The state led a push for coal as an energy source, even though there were reservations about its adverse environmental effects.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The oil shock destroyed the economy of South Vietnam.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] A spokesman for President Nguyễn Văn Thiệu admitted in a TV interview that the government was being "overwhelmed" by the inflation caused by the oil shock.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] An American businessman living in Saigon stated after the oil shock, that attempting to make money in South Vietnam was "like making love to a corpse".
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In December 1973, Vietcong sappers attacked and destroyed the petroleum depot of Nha Be, further depleting fuel sources.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] By the summer of 1974, the US embassy in Saigon reported that morale in the ARVN (Army of the Republic of Vietnam) had fallen to dangerously low levels and it was uncertain how much more longer South Vietnam would last.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] As inflation eroded the value of the South Vietnamese *đồng*, it became common by the summer of 1974 to see ARVN soldiers and their families begging in the streets for food.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] In December 1974, the North Vietnamese PAVN (People's Army of Vietnam) launched an offensive in the Central Highlands that was far more successful than expected, due to the ARVN's low morale and weak resistance.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] On March 1, 1975, the PAVN launched a major offensive that quickly overran the Central Highlands.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Following their victory in the Central Highlands, the North Vietnamese launched the "Ho Chi Minh Campaign" that captured Saigon on April 30, 1975.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Three of the nations targeted by the embargo were located in southern Africa or had colonies there.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Portugal which ruled the colonies of Angola, Portuguese Guiana (modern Guinea-Bissau), and Portuguese East Africa (modern Mozambique) had fighting colonial wars in all of its African colonies since the 1960s with Angola being the first to rise up in 1961.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Angola is rich in oil, which protected Portugal from the worse of the embargo.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] But the economic stability of the *Estado Novo* regime was damaged by the worldwide inflation, which help cause the Carnation Revolution which toppled the *Estado Novo* regime in April 1974 and led to the restoration of democracy.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Portugal granted independence to all of its colonies except for Macau in 1975.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The British historian Rob Skinner wrote the embargo had a "significant impact" on the South African economy.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The inflationary rise in commodity prices increased the input costs of South African manufacturing, making South African manufactured goods uncompetitive on the world market.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The rise in the price of gold as a hedge against inflation (South Africa has the world's largest gold mines) caused the *rand* to increase in value, which caused further problems for South African manufacturing.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The strategy pursued by the National Party government since 1948 of sponsoring the industrialization of South Africa was derailed by the oil shock, with what Skinner described as "important social and political consequences" for the *apartheid* regime.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The Soweto uprising of 1976 was at least in part caused by anger at the high unemployment rate in the black South African community.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Even worse hit than South Africa was Rhodesia (modern Zimbabwe), where oil was already expensive as the white supremacist government of Rhodesia had been under United Nations sanctions since 1965, and thus the smugglers who sold Rhodesia oil charged a premium for their services.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The premium charged by the "sanctions busters" such as Iran increased after the embargo, which threw the Rhodesian economy into recession.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Despite the United Nations sanctions, Rhodesia was a major exporter of chrome, steel and tobacco with the United States exempting "strategical" Rhodesian products such as chrome from the sanctions.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] The global recession of 1973–1975 proved more effective than the United Nations in ending the global demand for Rhodesian products, which made the Rhodesian recession especially severe.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Unlike South Africa, which had a sizable and long-standing white population, the white population of Rhodesia was much smaller and more recent.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p02] Rhodesia depended considerably more than South Africa on white immigration to provide enough soldiers for its army, while most of the Rhodesian whites had only arrived in the 1950s and did not have very deep roots in the country.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The white flight caused by the recession put the Rhodesian Army at a major disadvantage in its war against the black guerrillas.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The war cost the Rhodesian government one million Rhodesian dollars per day by 1975, and the costs of the war threatened to bankrupt Rhodesia.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1979, Rhodesia signed the Lancaster House Agreement, which led to Black majority rule in 1980.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Price controls exacerbated the crisis in the US.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The system limited the price of "old oil", that which had already been discovered, while allowing newly discovered oil to be sold at a higher price, to encourage investment.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a result, old oil was withdrawn from the market, creating greater scarcity.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The rule also discouraged development of alternative energies.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The rule had been intended to promote oil exploration.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Scarcity was addressed by rationing, as in many countries.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Motorists faced long lines at gas stations beginning in summer 1972 and increasing by summer 1973.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A sign of the change caused by the crisis was that in 1974 the Exxon oil company replaced the General Motors corporation to be the largest corporation in the world, as measured by gross sales revenues.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Simon as the first Administrator of the Federal Energy Office, a short-term organization created to coordinate the response to the embargo.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Simon allocated states the same amount of domestic oil for 1974 that each had consumed in 1972, which worked for states whose populations were not increasing.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In other states, lines at gasoline stations were common.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The American Automobile Association reported that in the last week of February 1974, 20% of American gasoline stations had no fuel.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Odd–even rationing allowed vehicles with license plates having an odd number as the last digit, or a vanity license plate, to buy gas only on odd-numbered days of the month.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Others could buy only on even-numbered days.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In some states, a three-color flag system was used to denote gasoline availability at service stations—green for unrationed availability, yellow for restricted/rationed sales, and red for out of stock.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Rationing led to violent incidents, when truck drivers chose to strike for two days in December 1973 over the limited supplies that Simon had allocated for their industry.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In Pennsylvania and Ohio, non-striking truckers were shot at by striking truckers.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In Arkansas, trucks of non-strikers were attacked with bombs.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] America had controlled the price of natural gas since the 1950s.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] With the inflation of the 1970s, the price was too low to encourage the search for new reserves.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] America's natural gas reserves dwindled from 237 trillion in 1974 to 203 trillion in 1978.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The price controls were not changed, despite president Gerald Ford's repeated requests to Congress.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] To help reduce consumption, in 1974 a national maximum speed limit of 55 mph (89 km/h) was imposed through the Emergency Highway Energy Conservation Act.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Development of the Strategic Petroleum Reserve began in 1975, and in 1977 the cabinet-level Department of Energy was created, followed by the National Energy Act of 1978.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In November 1995, President Bill Clinton signed the National Highway Designation Act, ending the federal 55 mph speed limit, which allowed states to restore their prior maximum speed limit.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Year-round daylight saving time was implemented from January 6, 1974, to October 27, 1975, with a break between October 27, 1974, and February 23, 1975, when the country observed standard time.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Parents complained that it forced many children to travel to school before sunrise.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The crisis prompted a call to conserve energy, most notably a campaign by the Advertising Council using the tagline "Don't Be Fuelish".
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Many newspapers carried advertisements featuring cut-outs that could be attached to light switches, reading "Last Out, Lights Out: Don't Be Fuelish".
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Although not regulated by the new legislation, auto racing groups voluntarily began conserving.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1974, NASCAR reduced all race distances by 10%; the 24 Hours of Daytona and the 12 Hours of Sebring race were cancelled.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1975, the Energy Policy and Conservation Act was passed, leading to the creation of the Corporate Average Fuel Economy (CAFE) standards that required improved fuel economy for cars and light trucks.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1976, Congress created the Weatherization Assistance Program to help low-income homeowners and renters reduce their demand for heating and cooling through better insulation.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1980, domestic luxury cars with a 130-inch (3.3 m) wheelbase and gross weights averaging 4,500 pounds (2,041 kg) were no longer made.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The automakers had begun phasing out the traditional front engine/rear-wheel drive layout in compact cars in favor of lighter front engine/front-wheel drive designs.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A higher percentage of cars offered more efficient four-cylinder engines.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Domestic auto makers also began offering more fuel efficient diesel powered passenger cars as well.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The energy crisis led to greater interest in renewable energy, nuclear power and domestic fossil fuels.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 2013, Peter Grossman opined that American energy policies after the crisis became and remained dominated by crisis-mentality thinking, promoting expensive quick fixes and single-shot solutions that ignore market and technology realities.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] He wrote that instead of providing stable rules that support basic research while leaving plenty of scope for entrepreneurship and innovation, Congresses and presidents repeatedly backed policies which promised politically expedient solutions whose true prospects were doubtful.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The Brazilian government implemented its Proálcool (pro-alcohol) project in 1975 that mixed ethanol with gasoline for automotive fuel.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Israel was one of the few countries unaffected by the embargo, since it could extract sufficient oil from the Sinai.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] But to supplement Israel's over-taxed power grid, Harry Zvi Tabor, the father of Israel's solar industry, developed the prototype for a solar water heater now used in over 90% of Israeli homes.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Western central banks decided to sharply cut interest rates to encourage growth, deciding that inflation was a secondary concern.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Although this was the orthodox macroeconomic prescription at the time, the resulting stagflation surprised economists and central bankers.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The policy is now considered by some to have deepened and lengthened the adverse effects of the embargo.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Recent research claims that in the period after 1985 the economy became more resilient to energy price increases.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The price shock created large current account deficits in oil-importing economies.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A petrodollar recycling mechanism was created, through which OPEC surplus funds were channeled through the capital markets to the West to finance the current account deficits.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The functioning of this mechanism required the relaxation of capital controls in oil-importing economies.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] It marked the beginning of an exponential growth of Western capital markets.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In the United States in 1974, seven of the 15 top Fortune 500 companies were oil companies, falling to four in 2014.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The crisis had a major impact on international relations and created a rift within NATO.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Some European nations and Japan sought to disassociate themselves from United States foreign policy in the Middle East to avoid being targeted by the boycott.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Arab oil producers linked any future policy changes to peace between the belligerents.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] To address this, the Nixon Administration began multilateral negotiations with the combatants.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] They arranged for Israel to pull back from the Sinai Peninsula and the Golan Heights.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By January 18, 1974, US Secretary of State Henry Kissinger had negotiated an Israeli troop withdrawal from parts of the Sinai Peninsula.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The promise of a negotiated settlement between Israel and Syria was enough to convince Arab oil producers to lift the embargo in March 1974. and again during the 1979 energy crisis.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] America's Cold War policies suffered a major blow from the embargo.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] They had focused on China and the Soviet Union, but the latent challenge to US hegemony coming from the Third World became evident.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 2004, declassified documents revealed that the US was so distraught by the rise in oil prices and being challenged by underdeveloped countries that they briefly considered military action to forcibly seize Middle Eastern oilfields in late 1973.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Western Europe began switching from pro-Israel to more pro-Arab policies.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] This change strained the Western alliance.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The US, which imported only 12% of its oil from the Middle East (compared with 80% for the Europeans and over 90% for Japan), remained staunchly committed to Israel.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The percentage of US oil which comes from the nations bordering the Persian Gulf remained steady over the decades, with a figure of a little more than 10% in 2008.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] With the embargo in place, many developed countries altered their policies regarding the Arab-Israeli conflict.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] These included the UK, which refused to allow the United States to use British bases and Cyprus to airlift resupplies to Israel, along with the rest of the members of the European Community.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Canada shifted towards a more pro-Arab position after displeasure was expressed towards Canada's mostly neutral position.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] "On the other hand, after the embargo the Canadian government moved quickly indeed toward the Arab position, despite its low dependence on Middle Eastern oil".
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Although lacking historical connections to the Middle East, Japan was the country most dependent on Arab oil.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] 71% of its imported oil came from the Middle East in 1970.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] On November 7, 1973, the Saudi and Kuwaiti governments declared Japan a "nonfriendly" country, to encourage it to change its noninvolvement policy.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] It received a 5% production cut in December, causing a panic.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] On November 22, Japan issued a statement "asserting that Israel should withdraw from all of the 1967 territories, advocating Palestinian self-determination, and threatening to reconsider its policy toward Israel if Israel refused to accept these preconditions".
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By December 25, Japan was considered an Arab-friendly state.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil embargo was announced roughly one month after a right-wing military coup in Chile led by General Augusto Pinochet toppled socialist president Salvador Allende on September 11, 1973.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The response of the Nixon administration was to propose doubling arms sales.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a consequence, an opposing Latin American bloc was organized and financed in part by Venezuelan oil revenues, which quadrupled between 1970 and 1975.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil shock disrupted the status quo relationships between Arab countries and the US and USSR.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] At the time, Egypt, Syria and Iraq were allied with the USSR.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia, Turkey and Iran, plus Israel, aligned with the US.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Vacillations in alignment often resulted in greater support from the respective superpowers.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] When Anwar Sadat became president of Egypt in 1970, he dismissed Soviet specialists in Egypt and reoriented towards the US.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Concerns over economic domination from increased Soviet oil production turned into fears of military aggression after the 1979 Soviet invasion of Afghanistan, a major turning point in Cold War geopolitics.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Persian Gulf states turned toward the US for security guarantees against Soviet military action, coming at a time marked by increased American weapons sales, technology, and outright military presence to various US-allied nations.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia and Iran became increasingly dependent on American security assurances to manage both external and internal threats, including increased military competition between them over increased oil revenues.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Both states were competing for preeminence in the Persian Gulf, and using increased revenues to fund expanded militaries.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1979, Saudi arms purchases from the US were five times larger than Israel's.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia is a near-absolute monarchy, an Arabic speaking country, and has a Sunni Muslim majority, while Persian speaking Iran since 1979 is an Islamist theocracy with a Shiite Muslim majority, which explains the current hostility between Saudi Arabia and Iran.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil crisis sent a signal to the auto industry globally, which changed many aspects of production and usage for decades to come.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] After World War II, most West European countries taxed motor fuel to limit imports, and as a result most cars made in Europe were smaller and more economical than their American counterparts.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By the late 1960s, increasing incomes supported rising car sizes.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The oil crisis pushed West European car buyers away from larger, less economical cars.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The most notable result of this transition was the rise in popularity of compact hatchbacks.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The only notable small hatchbacks built in Western Europe before the oil crisis were the Peugeot 104, Renault 5 and Fiat 127.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By the end of the decade, the market had expanded with the introduction of the Ford Fiesta, Opel Kadett (sold as the Vauxhall Astra in Great Britain), Chrysler Sunbeam and Citroën Visa.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Buyers looking for larger cars were increasingly drawn to medium-sized hatchbacks.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Virtually unknown in Europe in 1973, by the end of the decade they were gradually replacing sedans as the mainstay of this sector.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Between 1973 and 1980, medium-sized hatchbacks were launched across Europe: the Chrysler/Simca Horizon, Fiat Ritmo (Strada in the UK), Ford Escort MK3, Renault 14, Volvo 340 / 360, Opel Kadett, and Volkswagen Golf.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] These cars were considerably more economical than the traditional saloons they were replacing, and attracted buyers who traditionally bought larger vehicles.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Some 15 years after the oil crisis, hatchbacks dominated most European small and medium car markets, and had gained a substantial share of the large family car market.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Before the energy crisis, large, heavy, and powerful cars were popular.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1971, the standard engine in a Chevrolet Caprice was a 400-cubic inch (6.5 liter) V8.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The wheelbase of this car was 121.5 inches (3,090 mm), and *Motor Trend*'s 1972 road test of the similar Chevrolet Impala achieved no more than 15 highway miles per gallon.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In the 15 years prior to the 1973 oil crisis, gasoline prices in the US had lagged well behind inflation.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The crisis reduced the demand for large cars.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Japanese imports became mass-market leaders with unibody construction and front-wheel drive, which became de facto standards.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] From Europe, the Volkswagen Beetle, the Volkswagen Fastback, the Renault 8, the Renault LeCar, and the Fiat Brava were successful.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Detroit responded with the Ford Pinto, the Ford Maverick, the Chevrolet Vega, the Chevrolet Nova, the Plymouth Valiant and the Plymouth Volaré.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] American Motors sold its homegrown Gremlin, Hornet and Pacer models.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] A decade after the 1973 oil crisis, Honda, Toyota and Nissan, affected by the 1981 voluntary export restraints, opened US assembly plants and established their luxury divisions (Acura, Lexus and Infiniti, respectively) to distinguish themselves from their mass-market brands.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Compact trucks were introduced, such as the Toyota Hilux and the Datsun Truck, followed by the Mazda Truck (sold as the Ford Courier), and the Isuzu-built Chevrolet LUV.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Mitsubishi rebranded its Forte as the Dodge D-50 a few years after the oil crisis.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Mazda, Mitsubishi and Isuzu had joint partnerships with Ford, Chrysler, and GM, respectively.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Later, the American makers introduced their domestic replacements (Ford Ranger, Dodge Dakota and the Chevrolet S10/GMC S-15), ending their captive import policy.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] An increase in imported cars into North America forced General Motors, Ford and Chrysler to introduce smaller and fuel-efficient models for domestic sales.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The Dodge Omni / Plymouth Horizon from Chrysler, the Ford Fiesta and the Chevrolet Chevette all had four-cylinder engines and room for at least four passengers by the late 1970s.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1985, the average American vehicle moved 17.4 miles per gallon, compared to 13.5 in 1970.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The improvements stayed, even though the price of a barrel of oil remained constant at $12 from 1974 to 1979.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Sales of large sedans for most makes, except Chrysler products, recovered within two model years of the 1973 crisis.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The Cadillac DeVille and Fleetwood, Buick Electra, Oldsmobile 98, Lincoln Continental, Mercury Marquis, and various other luxury oriented sedans became popular again in the mid-1970s.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The only full-size models that did not recover were lower price models such as the Chevrolet Bel Air and Ford Galaxie 500.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Slightly smaller models such as the Oldsmobile Cutlass, Chevrolet Monte Carlo, Ford Thunderbird and various others sold well.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Economical imports succeeded alongside heavy, expensive vehicles.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In 1976, Toyota sold 346,920 cars (average weight around 2,100 lbs), while Cadillac sold 309,139 cars (average weight around 5,000 lbs).
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Federal safety standards, such as NHTSA Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standard 215 (pertaining to safety bumpers), and compacts like the 1974 Mustang I were a prelude to the DOT "downsize" revision of vehicle categories.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1977, GM's full-sized cars reflected the crisis.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1979, virtually all "full-size" American cars had shrunk, featuring smaller engines and smaller outside dimensions.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Chrysler ended production of their full-sized luxury sedans at the end of the 1981 model year, moving instead to a full front-wheel drive lineup for 1982, except for the M-body Dodge Diplomat/Plymouth Gran Fury and Chrysler New Yorker Fifth Avenue sedans.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] OPEC soon lost its preeminent position, and in 1981, its production was surpassed by that of other countries.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Additionally, its own member nations were divided.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Saudi Arabia, trying to recover market share, increased production, pushing prices down, shrinking or eliminating profits for high-cost producers.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The world price, which had peaked during the 1979 energy crisis at nearly $40 per barrel, decreased during the 1980s to less than $10 per barrel.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Adjusted for inflation, oil briefly fell back to pre-1973 levels.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] This "sale" price was a windfall for oil-importing nations, both developing and developed.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] During the Iran–Iraq War of 1980–1988, the stated war aim of Iran was to overthrow the Baath regime in Iraq.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a consequence, Saudi Arabia and the other Arab Gulf states leaned in a very pro-Iraqi neutrality during the war.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As a part of its policy of supporting Iraq, Saudi Arabia pumped out oil in massive quantities to lower the price as a way of hurting Iran's economy.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The low price of oil also hurt Iraq's economy, which forced Iraq to borrow massive sums of money, putting Iraq deeply into debt.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] In contrast, Iran refused to borrow any money because of its refusal to pay interest on any loans, and paid the costs of the war directly from the sale of its oil.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Iran's revenue from the sale of oil went from $20 billion US dollars per year in 1982 to $5 billion US dollars per year by 1988, which pushed Iran to the verge of bankruptcy and forced Iran to make peace with Iraq later in 1988.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] During the war, the Iranian delegation at OPEC tried very hard to have the group cut production to raise prices, but were blocked by the other delegations led by the Saudi delegation, who insisted on more oil production.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The embargo encouraged new venues for energy exploration, including Alaska, the North Sea, the Caspian Sea, and the Caucasus.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Exploration in the Caspian Basin and Siberia became profitable.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Cooperation changed into a far more adversarial relationship as the USSR increased its production.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] By 1980, the Soviet Union had become the world's largest producer.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Part of the decline in prices and economic and geopolitical power of OPEC came from the move to alternative energy sources.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] OPEC had relied on price inelasticity to maintain high consumption, but had underestimated the extent to which conservation and other sources of supply would eventually reduce demand.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Electricity generation from nuclear power and natural gas, home heating from natural gas, and ethanol-blended gasoline all reduced the demand for oil.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The drop in prices presented a serious problem for oil-exporting countries in northern Europe and the Persian Gulf.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Heavily populated, impoverished countries, whose economies were largely dependent on oil—including Mexico, Nigeria, Algeria, and Libya—did not prepare for a market reversal that left them in sometimes desperate situations.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] When reduced demand and increased production glutted the world market in the mid-1980s, oil prices plummeted and the cartel lost its unity.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] Mexico (a non-member), Nigeria, and Venezuela, whose economies had expanded in the 1970s, faced near-bankruptcy, and even Saudi Arabian economic power was significantly weakened.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] The divisions within OPEC made concerted action more difficult.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-oil-crisis-p03] As of 2015, OPEC has never approached its earlier dominance.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-soviet-economic-reform] The **1973 Soviet economic reform** was an economic reform initiated by Alexei Kosygin, the Chairman of the Council of Ministers.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-soviet-economic-reform] During Leonid Brezhnev's rule of the Union of Soviet Socialist Republics (USSR), the Soviet economy began to stagnate; this period is referred to by some historians as the Era of Stagnation.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-soviet-economic-reform] After the failed 1965 reform Kosygin initiated another reform in 1973 to enhance the powers and functions of the regional planners by establishing associations.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-soviet-economic-reform] The reform was never fully implemented, and members of the Soviet leadership complained that the reform had not even been fully implemented by the time of the 1979 reform.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-soviet-economic-reform] Alexei Kosygin's intention with the reform was to indirectly weaken the powers and functions of the central Ministries by establishing associations at the republican and local level of government.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-soviet-economic-reform] The newly established associations were to increase co-operation between enterprises on such important matters as technology, innovation, and education.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-soviet-economic-reform] A typical inefficiency with Soviet planning was that each enterprise was burdened by excessive production.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-soviet-economic-reform] New associations and agencies were still being established in 1980s, a decade after the reform was initiated.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-soviet-economic-reform] High-standing Soviet officials commented on the problem when the 1979 reform was initiated.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-soviet-economic-reform] Local planners and economists in the 1980s still complained that they had too little power in the daily running of their local economies.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-soviet-economic-reform] Specialised literature proved that the reform's main goal had failed to meet the expected standards.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-soviet-economic-reform] If the reform had been fully implemented it would have given republican and local-level associations considerable more leeway in economic management.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-soviet-economic-reform] The reform would have increased the influence of the political leadership and the State Planning Committee (Gosplan).
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-soviet-economic-reform] Historian Jan Åke Dellenbrant notes that an "unofficial reason" for the reform was to intentionally weaken the central Ministries, which had been accused of halting economic progress.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-soviet-economic-reform] The merging of enterprises into associations was accomplished by a highly controversial campaign by Soviet standards.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-soviet-economic-reform] The campaign was carried out in a spirit of derationalisation, which aggravated and even hurt the plan's highly rational goals.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-soviet-economic-reform] The industrial structure of the economy became even more derationalised and therefore more complicated.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-soviet-economic-reform] Central Ministries objected to the loss of enterprises by the setting up of associations, and enterprise managers disliked giving up most of their authority to association chairmen.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-soviet-economic-reform] Local party officials were skeptical of turning plants into local subsidiaries, because the plants' output would not be included in the republics' or regional yearly output statistics.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-soviet-economic-reform] Another problem was that local party cells claimed that they were informed too late about the reform's implementation.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-soviet-economic-reform] The reform had the side effect of weakening the powers of regional planners over industrial policy even further.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-soviet-economic-reform] By 1981, roughly half of Soviet industry had been merged into associations with an average of four member enterprises in each association.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-soviet-economic-reform] A problem was that an association usually had its members spread over different raions, oblasts, and even republics, which aggravated the State Planning Committee's localisation planning.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-soviet-economic-reform] The newly established associations made the Soviet economic system even more complex.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-soviet-economic-reform] The Gor'kii plant did not share the same problems as some other associations, as all its members were located in the same city.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-soviet-economic-reform] The relations between an association and the PPO were much more strained if the association had members over a wide geographic area.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-soviet-economic-reform] The reform had the effect of disrupting the CPSU's traditional allocation of resources between territorial and industrial agencies.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1973-soviet-economic-reform] *Kommunist*, a Soviet newspaper, noted that PPOs that supervised associations with members over a wide geographic area tended to lose touch with the local party and factory organisations, which prevented them from working effectively.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The **1977 Constitution of the Soviet Union**, officially the **Constitution of the Union of Soviet Socialist Republics**, was the communist state constitution adopted on 7 October 1977.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The 1977 Constitution replaced the 1936 Constitution and the Soviet public holiday of USSR Constitution Day was shifted from 5 December to 7 October.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The 1977 Constitution's preamble stated that "the aims of the dictatorship of the proletariat having been fulfilled, the Soviet state has become the state of the whole people" and no longer represented the workers and peasants alone.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The 1977 Constitution extended the scope of the constitutional regulation of society compared to the 1924 and 1936 constitutions.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The first chapter defined the leading role of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union (CPSU) and established the organizational principles for the state and the government.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The 1977 Constitution was long and detailed, including twenty-eight more articles than the 1936 Soviet Constitution and explicitly defined the division of responsibilities between the central government of the Soviet Union in Moscow and the governments of the republics.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] Later chapters established principles for economic management and cultural relations.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The 1977 Constitution included Article 72, which granted the official right of constituent republics to secede from the Soviet Union promised in previous constitutions.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] However, Articles 74 and 75 stated that when a Soviet constituency introduced laws in contradiction to Supreme Soviet, the laws of the Supreme Soviet would supersede any legal difference, but the Union law which regulated the secession was not provided until the last days of the Soviet Union.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The 1977 Constitution was repealed upon the dissolution of the Soviet Union on 26 December 1991 and the post-Soviet states adopted new constitutions.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] Article 72 would play an important role in the dissolution despite the lacuna in the Soviet law, which was eventually filled under the pressure from the Republics in 1990.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] Adoption of the Constitution was a legislative act of the Supreme Soviet.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] Amendments to the Constitution were likewise adopted by legislative act of that body.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] In addition, the governing bodies of official organizations and even the Academy of Sciences could initiate amendments and other legislation.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The principal source of uncensored information and comment in the USSR noted in August 1977 that the proposed Constitution "has given rise to a number of letters containing serious comments and well-argued proposals.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] Although these letters were sent to the Constitution Commission, not one of them was even mentioned in the Soviet newspapers or official media," it is quite possible that, like the letters department of all major Soviet periodicals, some note was privately taken of these views.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] Soviet constitutions were frequently amended and had been changed more often than the constitutions of most Western countries.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] Other enabling legislation has included a law on citizenship, a law on elections to the Supreme Soviet, a law on the status of Supreme Soviet deputies, regulations for the Supreme Soviet, a resolution on commissions, regulations on local government, and laws on the Supreme Court and the Procuracy.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The enabling legislation provided the specific and changing operating rules for these government bodies.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] In October 1988, draft amendments and additions to the 1977 Constitution were published in the Soviet media for public discussion.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] Following the public review process, the Supreme Soviet adopted the amendments and additions in December 1988.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The amendments and additions substantially and fundamentally changed the electoral and political systems.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] Although Soviet officials touted the changes as a return to "Leninist" forms and functions, citing that the Congress of People's Deputies had antecedents in the Congress of Soviets, they were unprecedented in many respects.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] Later still, the chairman of the Supreme Soviet's non-legislative powers would be transferred to the newly created office of President.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The Constitutional Oversight Committee, composed of people who were not in the Congress of People's Deputies, was established and given formal power to review the constitutionality of laws and normative acts of the central and republican governments and to suggest their suspension and repeal.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The electoral process was constitutionally opened up to multiple candidacies, although not multi-party candidacies.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] A legislative body—the Supreme Soviet—was to convene for regular spring and fall sessions, each lasting three to four months.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] Unlike the old Supreme Soviet, however, the new Supreme Soviet was indirectly elected by the population, being elected from among the members of the Congress of People's Deputies.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The Soviet Constitution included a series of civil and political rights.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] Among these were the rights to freedom of speech, freedom of the press, and freedom of assembly and the right to religious belief and worship.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] In addition, the Constitution provided for freedom of artistic work, protection of the family, inviolability of the person and home, and the right to privacy.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] In line with the Marxist-Leninist ideology of the government, the Constitution also granted social and economic rights not provided by constitutions in some capitalist countries.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] Among these were the rights to work, rest and leisure, health protection, care in old age and sickness, housing, education, and cultural benefits.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] Unlike Western constitutions, the Soviet Constitution outlined limitations on political rights, whereas in capitalist countries these limitations are usually left up to the legislative and/or judicial institutions.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] Article 6 effectively eliminated partisan opposition and division within government by granting to the CPSU the power to lead and guide society.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The government did not treat as inalienable those political and socioeconomic rights the Constitution granted to the people.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] Citizens enjoyed rights only when the exercise of those rights did not interfere with the interests of the state, and the CPSU alone had the power and authority to determine policies for the government and society.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] For example, the right to freedom of expression stipulated in Article 52 could be suspended if the exercise of that freedom failed to be in accord with Party policies.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] Until the era of *glasnost*, freedom of expression did not entail the right to criticize the government.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The constitution did provide a "freedom of conscience, that is, the right to profess or not to profess any religion, and to conduct religious worship or atheistic propaganda." It prohibited incitement of hatred or hostility on religious grounds.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The Constitution also failed to provide political and judicial mechanisms for the protection of rights.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] Thus, the Constitution lacked explicit guarantees protecting the rights of the people.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] In fact, the Supreme Soviet never introduced amendments specifically designed to protect human rights.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] Neither did the people have a higher authority within the government to which to appeal when their rights were violated.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] Unlike in a democratic system, there was no constitutional court with the power to ensure that constitutional rights were observed by legislation or were respected by the rest of the government.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] Article 59 of the Constitution stated that citizens' exercise of their rights was inseparable from performance of their duties.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] Articles 60 through 69 defined these duties.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] Citizens were required to work and to observe labor discipline.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The legal code declared evasion of work to be a crime of "parasitism" and provided punishment for it.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The Constitution also obliged citizens to protect socialist property and oppose corruption.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] All citizens performed military service as a duty to safeguard and "enhance the power and prestige of the Soviet state." Violation of this duty was considered "a betrayal of the Motherland and the gravest of crimes".
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] Finally, the Constitution required parents to train their children for socially useful work and to raise them to be worthy members of the socialist society.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] The Constitution and other legislation protected and enforced Soviet citizenship.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] Legislation on citizenship granted equal rights of citizenship to naturalized citizens as well as to the native born.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] Laws also specified that citizens could not freely renounce their citizenship.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] Citizens were required to apply for permission to do so from the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet, which could reject the application if the applicant had not completed military service, had judicial duties, or was responsible for family dependants.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-constitution-of-the-soviet-union] In addition, the Presidium could refuse the application to protect national security, or revoke citizenship for defamation of the Soviet Union or for acts damaging to national prestige or security.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-moscow-bombings] A series of three terrorist bombings in Moscow on 8 January 1977 killed seven people and seriously injured 37 others.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-moscow-bombings] No one claimed responsibility for the bombings, although three members of an Armenian nationalist organization were executed early in 1979 after a KGB investigation and a secret trial.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-moscow-bombings] Some Soviet dissidents said that the suspects had an alibi.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-moscow-bombings] Soon after the event Andrei Sakharov issued a public appeal, expressing concern that the bombings might "be a new provocation on the part of the organs of repression".
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-moscow-bombings] According to historian Jay Bergman, "who actually caused the explosion has never been determined conclusively".
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-moscow-bombings] On 8 January 1977, three bombs were detonated in Moscow.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-moscow-bombings] The first exploded at 17:33 on a crowded train between the Izmailovskaya and Pervomaiskaya stations of the Moscow Metro.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-moscow-bombings] At 18:05, the second bomb detonated inside a grocery store close to KGB headquarters.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-moscow-bombings] Five minutes later, the third bomb exploded near another grocery store on 25 October Street, just a few hundred meters away from the headquarters of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-moscow-bombings] At that moment, and for the next two months, there was little public information about the explosions.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-moscow-bombings] The TASS news agency reported on 10 January 1977 that the explosion was not of great force, "medical help was given to those suffering injury, and an investigation is being conducted".
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-moscow-bombings] Later, at meetings of Party activists, it was said that not long before the explosion in the underground on 8 January there had been two other explosions on 25 October Street.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-moscow-bombings] Only on 8 February 1979, after the trial and execution of the three convicted men, did a letter to *Izvestia*, the official newspaper of the Soviet government, indicate that the attacks had killed seven people and injured 37.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-moscow-bombings] An initial suspect, named Potapov, was arrested in Tambov after setting off a bomb which killed his neighbour's wife and two daughters.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-moscow-bombings] After being arrested, Potapov confessed that he was also behind the acts of terrorism in Moscow.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-moscow-bombings] However, this turned out to have been a forced confession, and after an investigation lasting one month, this lead was dropped by KGB operatives.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-moscow-bombings] In October 1977, at Tashkent Airport, a KGB officer noticed a woman carrying a bag similar to a reconstructed picture of a bomb sent by the KGB to all local branches.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-moscow-bombings] It was discovered that these bags were manufactured only in Yerevan.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-moscow-bombings] In November 1977, Stepan Zatikyan, a founding member of a splinter group of the National United Party, an underground Armenian nationalist organization, was arrested.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-moscow-bombings] His accomplices, Zaven Bagdasaryan and Hakop Stepanyan, were also taken into custody after an unsuccessful attempt to detonate a bomb at the Kursky Rail Terminal in Moscow.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-moscow-bombings] Zatikyan, Stepanyan, and Bagdasaryan were all found guilty on 24 January 1978 and executed five days later.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-moscow-bombings] The Supreme Court issued a brief statement, dated 31 January 1979, after the trial and execution, naming Zatikyan alone as the perpetrator.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-moscow-bombings] According to KGB general Philip Bobkov, any publications in Armenia about the bombings were blocked by Karen Demirchyan, the head of Soviet Armenia.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-moscow-bombings] The 8 January 1977 bombings occurred during systematic reprisals by the Soviet authorities against the Helsinki Groups in Moscow, Ukraine and Lithuania, set up to monitor the USSR's observance of the Helsinki Accords.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-moscow-bombings] On 10 January 1977, Soviet journalist Victor Louis (Vitaly Yevgenyevich Lui), a well-known KGB agent provocateur, published an article in a British newspaper, hinting at the involvement of Soviet dissidents in the bombings.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-moscow-bombings] Several dissidents, including Vladimir Albrekht, the secretary of the Soviet branch of Amnesty International, were threatened and interrogated by the KGB.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-moscow-bombings] (Soviet dissident Alexander Tarasov claimed to have been interrogated by a KGB investigator who tried to "convince" him that he was involved in the bombing.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-moscow-bombings] In an exchange with the deputy procurator general, he added, "I have serious grounds for concern.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-moscow-bombings] This is the provocation article in *London Evening News* by Victor Lui.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-moscow-bombings] These are arrests and interrogations of people who are clearly not related to the bombings.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-moscow-bombings] These are murders of last months, probably committed by the KGB which were not investigated.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-moscow-bombings] It is enough to mention only two of them: murder of poet Konstantin Bogatyrev and murder of lawyer Evgeni Brunov." After this statement, Sakharov was not only attacked in Soviet newspapers but also received threats by phone.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-moscow-bombings] Several people tried to break into his apartment, claiming to be relatives of those killed in the metro.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-moscow-bombings] According to former KGB colonel Oleg Gordievsky, the three Armenians were selected as scapegoats for this terrorist act.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-moscow-bombings] He wrote, "The case that most alarmed the KGB was the bombing of the Moscow subway by Armenian separatists in 1977.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-moscow-bombings] In 1982, historians Michel Heller and Alexander Nekrich asserted Zatikyan, Stepanyan, and Bagdasaryan had an alibi supported by multiple witnesses, and their execution was the first political execution in the Soviet Union after the death of Stalin.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-moscow-bombings] The Armenian dissident Sergei Grigoryants said in 2016 that KGB chief Yuri Andropov and Philipp Bobkov were responsible for the bombings.
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-moscow-bombings] On 1 February 1979, the Moscow Helsinki Group made an official statement on the execution of Zatikyan and two unnamed individuals, stating, "The lack of transparency and the whole atmosphere of secrecy give reasons to doubt the validity of charges, objectivity and impartiality of the court".
[src:alexei-kosygin/1977-moscow-bombings] One consequence was the 8 February 1979 letter to Izvestia, denouncing Sakharov and other rights activists as "defenders of murderers".
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Alexei Kosygin was born in the city of Saint Petersburg in 1904 to a Russian working-class family.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] During the Russian Civil War, he was conscripted into the labour army.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] After the Red Army's demobilization in 1921, he worked in Siberia as an industrial manager.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] In the early 1930s, Kosygin returned to Leningrad and worked his way up the Soviet hierarchy.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] During the Great Patriotic War (World War II), Kosygin was tasked by the State Defence Committee with moving Soviet industry out of territories soon to be overrun by the German Army.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] He served as Minister of Finance for a year before becoming Minister of Light Industry (later, Minister of Light Industry and Food).
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] However, in 1952, Stalin removed Kosygin from the Politburo, thereby weakening Kosygin's position within the Soviet hierarchy.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Following Stalin's death in 1953, Kosygin was appointed chairman of the State Planning Committee (Gosplan) on 20 March 1959.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Later, in 1960, he was promoted to First Deputy Chairman of the Council of Ministers.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] When Nikita Khrushchev was removed from power on 14 October 1964, Kosygin and Leonid Brezhnev succeeded him as Chairman of the Council of Ministers and First Secretary of the Communist Party respectively.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Thereafter, he formed a triumvirate alongside Brezhnev and Central Committee Secretary Nikolai Podgorny that led the Soviet regime in Khrushchev's place.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Upon Khrushchev's ouster, Alexei Kosygin initially emerged as the Soviet Union's head of government in both name and practice.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] In addition to overseeing the country's economy, he assumed a preeminent role in directing its foreign policy.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] However, in 1968, the Prague Spring triggered a massive backlash against his reforms, thereby enabling Leonid Brezhnev to eclipse him as the dominant force in the Soviet leadership.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Despite having his standing significantly weakened in the Kremlin, Kosygin was permitted by Brezhnev to remain in office until his retirement on 15 October 1980 due to bad health.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] He died two months later on 18 December 1980.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Kosygin was born into a Russian working-class family consisting of his father and mother (Nikolai Ilyich and Matrona Alexandrovna) and his siblings.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Kosygin was baptized (7 March 1904) one month after his birth.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] He lost his mother in infancy and was brought up by his father.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] He and his father sympathized with the Revolution and Alexei was conscripted into a labour army on the Bolshevik side at the age of 14 during the Russian Civil War of 1917–1922.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] After demobilization from the Red Army in 1921, Kosygin attended the Leningrad Co-operative Technical School and found work in the system of consumer co-operatives in Novosibirsk, Siberia.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] He applied for a membership in the Communist Party of the Soviet Union in 1927 and returned to Leningrad in 1930 to study at the Leningrad Textile Institute; he graduated in 1935.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] After finishing his studies, Kosygin worked as a foreman and later a manager as a textile mill director.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] He rose rapidly during the Great Purge, overseen in Leningrad by the provincial communist party boss, Andrei Zhdanov.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] He was appointed director of the October Textile Factory in 1937, head of the Industry and Transport department of the Leningrad provincial communist party in July 1938, and in October 1938, Chairman of the Executive Committee of the Leningrad City Soviets of Working People's Deputies, i.e.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] In 1939, he was appointed People's Commissar for Textile and Industry and earned a seat on the Central Committee (CC).
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] In 1940 Kosygin became a Deputy Chairman of the Council of People's Commissars.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Kosygin was appointed by the State Defence Committee to manage critically important missions during the Great Patriotic War (World War II).
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] As deputy chairman of the Council of Evacuation, he had the task of evacuating industry from territories about to be overrun by the Axis.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Under his command 1,523 factories were evacuated eastwards, as well as huge volumes of raw materials, ready-made goods and equipment.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Kosygin managed clearing of congestions on the railways in order to maintain their stable operation.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] During the Leningrad Blockade he was sent to his hometown to manage the construction of an ice road and a pipeline across Lake Ladoga.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] This allowed to evacuate some half million people from the besieged and starving city, and to supply fuel to its factories and power plants.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] He was also responsible for the procurement of locally available firewood.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] In 1943 Alexey Kosygin was promoted to Chairman of the Council of People's Commissars (government) of the Russian SFSR.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] In 1944 he was appointed to head the Currency Board of the Soviet Union.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Kosygin became a candidate member of the Politburo in 1946.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] During the Soviet famine of 1946–47 he headed the foodstuff relief missions to the most suffering regions.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] He was appointed USSR Minister for Finance in February 1948, and a full member of the Politburo on 4 September 1948, putting him among the dozen or so most ranking officials in the USSR.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Kosygin's administrative skills led Stalin to take the younger man under his wing.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Stalin shared information with Kosygin, such as how much money the families of Vyacheslav Molotov, Anastas Mikoyan, and Lazar Kaganovich possessed, spent and paid their staff.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] (A Politburo member earned a modest salary by Soviet standards but enjoyed unlimited access to consumer goods.) Stalin sent Kosygin to each home to put their houses into "proper order".
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Kosygin's patron, Zhdanov, died suddenly in August 1948.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] During the brutal purge that followed, known as the Leningrad affair, Voznesensky, Kuznetsov and many others were arrested and shot.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Kosygin was relegated to the post of USSR Minister for Light Industry, while nominally retaining his membership of the Politburo until 1952.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Kosygin told his son-in-law Mikhail Gvishiani, an NKVD officer, of the accusations leveled against Voznesensky because of his possession of firearms.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Gvishiani and Kosygin threw all their weapons into a lake and searched both their own houses for any listening devices.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] They found one at Kosygin's house, but it might have been installed to spy on Marshal Georgy Zhukov, who had lived there before him.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] According to his memoirs, Kosygin never left his home without reminding his wife what to do if he did not return from work.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] After living two years in constant fear, the family reached the conclusion that Stalin would not harm them.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] However, despite Khrushchev's reluctance, Kosygin's career made a steady recovery.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] In June 1957, he was again appointed a Deputy Chairman of the Council of Ministers (for the third time), and a candidate member of the Presidium Central Committee (the renamed Politburo).
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] In March 1959, he was made Chairman of Gosplan, and on 4 May 1960, he was promoted to First Deputy Chairman of the Council of Ministers, and a full member of the Presidium.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] As First Deputy Premier Kosygin travelled abroad, mostly on trade missions, to countries such as North Korea, India, Argentina and Italy.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Since 1959 Kosygin headed the Soviet mission to the ComEcon.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Later, in the aftermath of the Cuban Missile Crisis, Kosygin was the Soviet spokesman for improved relations between the Soviet Union and the United States.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] When Khrushchev was removed from power in October 1964, Kosygin replaced him as Premier as part of a collective leadership dynamic that included Leonid Brezhnev as general secretary and Nikolai Podgorny who ultimately became Chairman of the Presidium.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Overall, the new Politburo adopted a more conservative outlook than that under Khrushchev's rule.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Kosygin, Podgorny and Andrei Kirilenko were the most reformist members of the new Soviet leadership.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Conversely, Brezhnev and Arvīds Pelše belonged to the moderate faction while Mikhail Suslov retained his leadership of the party's Stalinist wing.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] In October 1964, at a ceremony in honour of Soviet cosmonauts, Brezhnev called for the strengthening of the Party apparatus.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] This speech was only the beginning of a large campaign directed against Kosygin.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Several newspapers, such as *Pravda* and *Kommunist*, criticized the work of the Council of Ministers, and indirectly Kosygin, its chairman, for planning the economy in an unrealistic fashion, and used the highly aggressive rhetoric previously used to condemn Khrushchev against Kosygin.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Brezhnev was able to criticize Kosygin by contrasting him with Vladimir Lenin, who – Brezhnev claimed – had been more interested in improving the conditions of Soviet agriculture than improving the quality of light industrial goods.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Kosygin's support for producing more consumer goods was also criticized by Brezhnev, and his supporters, most notably Konstantin Chernenko, for being a return to quasi First World policies.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] At the 23rd Party Congress, Kosygin's position was weakened when Brezhnev's supporters were able to increase expenditure on defense and agriculture.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] However, Brezhnev did not have a majority in the Politburo, and could count on only four votes.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] In the Politburo, Kosygin could count on Kiril Mazurov's vote, and when Kosygin and Podgorny were not bickering with each other, they actually had a majority in the Politburo over Brezhnev.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Unfortunately for Kosygin this was not often the case, and Kosygin and Podgorny were constantly disagreeing on policy.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Kosygin's position in the Soviet leadership was ultimately weakened following his enactment of several economic initiatives in 1965 that collectively came to be known within the Party as the "Kosygin reforms".
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Due largely to coinciding with the political upheaval created by the Prague Spring, the reforms provoked a backlash among the party's old guard who proceeded to flock to Brezhnev and strengthen his position within the Soviet leadership.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] By March 1971, it became apparent that Brezhnev was the leader of the country, with Kosygin as the spokesman of the five-year plan and Podgorny's position within the collective leadership strengthened.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Early on in his tenure, Kosygin challenged Brezhnev's right as general secretary to represent the country abroad, a function Kosygin believed should fall into the hands of the head of government, as was common in non-communist countries.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] This was actually implemented for a short period, which led Henry A.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Kissinger to believe that Kosygin was the leader of the Soviet Union.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Kosygin, who had been the chief negotiator with the First World during the 1960s, was hardly seen outside the Second World after Brezhnev consolidated his position within the Politburo, but also due to Foreign Minister Andrei Gromyko's dislike of Kosygin meddling into his own ministerial affairs.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] The Six-Day War in the Middle East had the effect of increasing Soviet–American cooperation; to improve relations even further, the United States Government invited Kosygin to a summit with Lyndon B.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Johnson, the President of the United States, following his speech to the United Nations.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] At the summit, which became known as the Glassboro Summit Conference, Johnson and Kosygin failed to reach agreement on limiting anti-ballistic missile systems, but the summit's friendly and even open atmosphere was referred to as the "Spirit of Glassboro".
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Relations between the two countries improved further when the 1970 Moscow Treaty was signed on 12 August 1970 by Kosygin, Gromyko, Willy Brandt and Walter Scheel who represented West Germany.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] In 1971, Kosygin gave an extensive interview to the American delegation that included David Rockefeller, presenting his views on US-Soviet relations, environmental protection, arms control and other issues.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Kosygin developed a close friendly relationship with the President of Finland Urho Kekkonen, which helped the USSR to maintain active mutual trade with Finland and to keep it away from Cold War confrontation.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] In 1972, Kosygin signed a Treaty of Friendship and Cooperation with the government of Iraq, building on strong Soviet ties to the Iraqi Arab Socialist Ba'ath Party and previous close relations with Iraqi leader Abd al-Karim Qasim.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Kosygin protected János Kádár's economic reforms and his position as leader of the Hungarian People's Republic from intervention by the Soviet leadership.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Polish leader Władysław Gomułka, who was removed from all of his posts in 1970, was succeeded by Edward Gierek who tried to revitalize the economy of the People's Republic of Poland by borrowing money from the First World.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] The Soviet leadership approved both countries' respective economic experiments, since it was trying to reduce its large Eastern Bloc subsidy programme in the form of cheap oil and gas exports.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] During the discussions within the Soviet leadership of a possible Soviet invasion of Czechoslovakia, Kosygin reminded leaders of the consequences of the Soviet suppression of the 1956 Hungarian revolution.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Kosygin's stance became more aggressive later on when he understood that the reforms in Czechoslovakia could be turned against his 1965 Soviet economic reform.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Kosygin acted as a mediator between India and Pakistan in 1966, and got both nations to sign the Tashkent Declaration.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Kosygin became the chief spokesman on the issue of arms control.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] In retrospect, many of Kosygin's colleagues felt he carried out his work "stoically", but lacked "enthusiasm", and therefore never developed a real taste for international politics.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] The Sino–Soviet split chagrined Kosygin a great deal, and for a while he refused to accept its irrevocability; he briefly visited Beijing in 1969 due to increased tension between the USSR and Maoist China.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Kosygin said, in a close-knit circle, that "We are communists and they are communists.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] It is hard to believe we will not be able to reach an agreement if we met face to face".
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] His view on China changed, however, and according to Harold Wilson, former Prime Minister of the United Kingdom, Kosygin viewed China as an "organized military dictatorship" whose intended goal was to enslave "Vietnam and the whole of Asia".
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] During an official visit by an Afghan delegation, Kosygin and Andrei Kirilenko criticized Afghan leaders Nur Muhammad Taraki and Hafizullah Amin for Stalinist-like repressionist behaviour.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] He promised to send more economic and military aid, but rejected any proposal regarding a possible Soviet intervention, as an intervention in Afghanistan would strain the USSR's foreign relations with the First World according to Kosygin, most notably West Germany.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] However, in a closed meeting, without Kosygin, who strongly opposed any kind of military intervention, the Politburo unanimously supported a Soviet intervention.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] The Eighth Five-Year Plan (1966–1970) is considered to be one of the most successful periods for the Soviet economy and the most successful when it comes to consumer production (see The "Kosygin" reform).
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] The 23rd Party Congress and the Ninth Five-Year Plan (1971–1975) had been postponed by Brezhnev due to a power struggle within the Soviet leadership.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] At the 23rd Party Congress, Kosygin promised that the Ninth Five-Year Plan would increase the supply of food, clothing and other household appliances up to 50 percent.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] The plan envisaged a massive increase in the Soviet standard of living, with Kosygin proclaiming a growth of 40 percent for the population's cash income in his speech to the congress.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] The Tenth Five-Year Plan (1976–1981) was referred to by Kosygin as the "plan of quality".
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Brezhnev rejected Kosygin's bid for producing more consumer goods during the Tenth Five-Year Plan.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] As a result, the total volume of consumer goods in industrial production only stood at 26 percent.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Kosygin's son-in-law notes that Kosygin was furious with the decision, and proclaimed increased defence expenditure would become the Soviet Union's "complete ruin".
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] The plan was less ambitious than its predecessors, with targets of national industrial growth no higher than what the rest of the world had already achieved.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Soviet agriculture would receive a share investment of 34 percent, a share much larger than its proportional contribution to the Soviet economy, as it accounted for only 3 percent of the Soviet GDP.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Like Khrushchev, Kosygin tried to reform the command economy within a socialist framework.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] In 1965 Kosygin initiated an economic reform widely referred to as the "Kosygin reform".
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] The reform had been proposed to Khrushchev in 1964, who evidently liked it and took some preliminary steps to implement it.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Brezhnev allowed the reform to proceed because the Soviet economy was entering a period of low growth.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] In its testing phase, the reform was applied to 336 enterprises in light industry.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] The reform was influenced by the works of Soviet economist Evsei Liberman.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Kosygin overestimated the ability of the Soviet administrative machine to develop the economy, which led to "corrections" to some of Liberman's more controversial beliefs about decentralization.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] According to critics, Kosygin's changes to Liberman's original vision caused the reform to fail.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Kosygin believed that decentralization, semi-public companies, and cooperatives were keys to catching up to the First World's contemporary level of economic growth.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] His reform sought a gradual change from a "state-administered economy" to an economy in which "the state restricts itself to guiding enterprises".
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] The reform was implemented, but showed several malfunctions and inconsistencies early on.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] The salary for Soviet citizens increased abruptly by almost 2.5 times during the plan.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Real wages in 1980 amounted to 232.7 rubles, compared to 166.3 rubles before the 1965 Soviet economic reform and the Eighth Five-Year Plan.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] The first period, 1960–1964, was characterized by low growth, while the second period, 1965–1981, had a stronger growth rate.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] The second period vividly demonstrated the success of the Kosygin reform, with the average annual growth in retail turnover being 11.2 billion rubles, 1.8 times higher than in the first period and 1.2 times higher than the third period (1981–1985).
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Consumption of goods and daily demand also increased.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] The consumption of home appliances greatly increased.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Refrigerators increased from a low of 109,000 in 1964 to 440,000 units by 1973; consumption declined during the reversal of the reform.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Car production increased, and would continue to do so until the late 1980s.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] The Soviet leadership, under pressure, sought to provide more attractive goods for Soviet consumers.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] The removal of Khrushchev in 1964 signalled the end of his "housing revolution".
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Housing construction declined between 1960 and 1964 to an average of 1.63 million square metres.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Following this sudden decrease, housing construction increased sharply between 1965 and 1966, but dropped again, and then steadily grew (the average annual growth rate was 4.26 million square metres).
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] This came largely at the expense of businesses.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] While the housing shortage was never fully resolved, and still remains a problem in present-day Russia, the reform overcame the negative trend and renewed the growth of housing construction.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Growing hostility towards reform, the initial poor results, and Kosygin's reformist stance, led to a popular backlash against him.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Kosygin lost most of the privileges he had enjoyed before the reform, but Brezhnev was never able to remove him from the office of Chairman of the Council of Ministers, despite his weakened position.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] In the aftermath of his failed reform, Kosygin spent the rest of his life improving the economic administration through the modification of targets; he implemented various programmes to improve food security and ensure the future intensification of production.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] There is no proof to back up the claim that the reform itself contributed to the high growth seen in the late-1960s, or that its cancellation had anything to do with the stagnating growth of the economy which began in the 1970s.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Kosygin initiated another economic reform in 1973 with the intention of weakening the central Ministries and giving more powers to the regional authorities at republican and local levels.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] The reform's failure to meet Kosygin's goal led to its cancellation.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] However, the reform succeeded in creating *associations*, an organization representing various enterprises.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] The last significant reform undertaken by the pre-*perestroika* leadership was initiated by Kosygin's fifth government in a joint decision of the Central Committee and the Council of Ministers.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] The "Improving planning and reinforcing the effects of the economic mechanism on raising the effectiveness in production and improving the quality of work", more commonly known as the 1979 reform.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] The reform, in contrast to the 1965 reform, was intended to increase the central government's economic involvement by enhancing the duties and responsibilities of the ministries.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Due to Kosygin's resignation in 1980, and because of Nikolai Tikhonov's conservative approach to economics, very little of the reform was actually implemented.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] By the early to mid-1970s Brezhnev had established a strong enough power base to effectively become leader.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] According to historian Ilya Zemtsov, the author of *Chernenko: The Last Bolshevik: The Soviet Union on the Eve of Perestroika*, Kosygin "began to lose power" with the 24th Party Congress in 1971, which for the first time publicized the formula 'the Politburo led by Brezhnev'".
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Along with weakening Kosygin's position, Brezhnev moved to strengthen the Party's hold on the Government apparatus, weakening Kosygin's position further.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Historian Robert Wesson, the author of *Lenin's Legacy: The Story of the CPSU*, notes that Kosygin's economic report to the 25th Party Congress "pointed even more clearly to the end of struggle" between Brezhnev and Kosygin.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Kosygin was further pushed aside when Brezhnev published his memoirs, which stated that Brezhnev, not Kosygin, was in charge of all major economic decisions.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] To make matters worse for Kosygin, Brezhnev blocked any future talks on economic reform within the party and government apparatus, and information regarding the reform of 1965 was suppressed.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Brezhnev consolidated his own position over the Government Apparatus by strengthening Podgorny's position as Chairman of the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet, literally head of state, by giving the office some of the functions of the Premier.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] The 1977 Soviet Constitution strengthened Podgorny's control of the Council of Ministers, by giving the post of head of state some executive powers.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] In fact, because of the 1977 Soviet Constitution, the Council of Ministers became subordinate to the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] When Podgorny was replaced as head of state in 1977 by Brezhnev, Kosygin's role in day-to-day management of government activities was lessened drastically, through Brezhnev's new-found post.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Rumours started circulating within the top circles, and on the streets, that Kosygin would retire due to bad health.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Brezhnev's consolidation of power weakened Kosygin's influence and prestige within the Politburo.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Kosygin's position was gradually weakened during the 1970s and he was frequently hospitalized.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] On several occasions Kiril Mazurov, the First Deputy Chairman of the Council of Ministers, had to act on his behalf.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Kosygin suffered his first heart attack in 1976.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] After this incident, it is said that Kosygin changed from having a vibrant personality to being tired and fed up; he, according to people close to him, seemed to have lost the will to continue his work.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] He twice filed a letter of resignation between 1976 and 1980, but was turned down on both occasions.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] During Kosygin's sick leave, Brezhnev appointed Nikolai Tikhonov to the post of First Deputy Chairman of the Council of Ministers.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Tikhonov, as with Brezhnev, was a conservative, and through his post as First Deputy Chairman Tikhonov was able to reduce Kosygin to a standby role.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] At a Central Committee plenum in June 1980, the Soviet economic development plan was outlined by Tikhonov, not Kosygin.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] The powers of the Premier diminished to the point where Kosygin was forced to discuss all decisions made by the Council of Ministers with Brezhnev.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Kosygin was hospitalized in October 1980.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] During his stay, on 23 October, he wrote a brief letter of resignation; the following day he was deprived of all government protection, communication, and luxury goods he had earned during his political life.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] When Kosygin died on 18 December 1980 in Moscow, none of his Politburo colleagues, former aides, or security guards visited him.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] At the end of his life, Kosygin feared the complete failure of the Eleventh Five-Year Plan (1981–1985), saying that the sitting leadership was reluctant to reform the stagnant Soviet economy.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] His funeral was postponed for three days, as Kosygin died on the eve of Brezhnev's birthday, and the day of Stalin's.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Kosygin was praised by Brezhnev as an individual who "laboured selflessly for the good of the Soviet state".
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] A state funeral was conducted and Kosygin was honoured by his peers; Brezhnev, Yuri Andropov, and Tikhonov laid an urn containing his ashes at the Kremlin Wall Necropolis.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Compared with other Soviet officials, Kosygin stood out as a pragmatic and relatively independent leader.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] He was a very alert man, and performed brilliantly during negotiations.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] He was able to cope quickly with the material that was totally new to him.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Canadian Prime Minister Pierre Trudeau said Kosygin was like "Khrushchev without the rough edges, a fatherly man who was the forerunner of Mikhail Gorbachev".
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] He noted that Kosygin was willing to discuss issues so long as the Soviet position was not tackled head-on.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Former United States Secretary of State Henry Kissinger said that Kosygin was devoted, nearly fanatically, to his work.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Kosygin was viewed by Western diplomats as a pragmatist "with a glacial exterior who was orthodox if not rigid".
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Andrei Sakharov, a Soviet dissident, believed Kosygin to be "the most intelligent and toughest man in the Politburo".
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Singapore Prime Minister Lee Kuan Yew remembered Kosygin as "very quiet-spoken, but very determined, mind of great ability and application".
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] US economist David Rockefeller described Kosygin as a talented manager doing miracles in ruling the clumsy Soviet economy.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Kosygin would prove to be a very competent administrator, with the Soviet standard of living rising considerably due to his moderately reformist policy.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Kosygin's moderate 1965 reform, as with Nikita Khrushchev's thaw, radicalized the Soviet reform movement.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] While Leonid Brezhnev was content to maintain the centralized structure of the Soviet planned economy, Kosygin attempted to revitalize the ailing economic system by decentralising management.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Following Brezhnev's death in 1982, the reform movement was split between Yuri Andropov's path of discipline and control and Gorbachev's liberalization of all aspects of public life.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Kosygin was viewed with sympathy by the Soviet people, and is still presently viewed as an important figure in both Russian and Soviet history.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Because of Kosygin's popularity among the Soviet people, Brezhnev developed a "strong jealousy" for Kosygin, according to Nikolai Egorychev.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Mikhail Smirtyukov, the former Executive Officer of the Council of Ministers, recalled that Kosygin refused to go drinking with Brezhnev, a move which annoyed Brezhnev gravely.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] Nikolai Ryzhkov, the last Chairman of the Council of Ministers, in a speech to the Supreme Soviet of the Soviet Union in 1987 referred to the "sad experiences of the 1965 reform", and claimed that everything went from bad to worse following the reform's cancellation.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] During his lifetime, Kosygin received seven Orders and two Awards from the Soviet state.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] He was awarded two Hero of Socialist Labour (USSR); one being on his 60th birthday by the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet in 1964, on this occasion he was also awarded an Order of Lenin and a Hammer and Sickle Gold Medal.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] On 20 February 1974, to commemorate his 70th birthday, the Presidium of the Supreme Soviet awarded him another Order of Lenin and his second Hammer and Sickle Gold Medal.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] In total, Kosygin was awarded six Orders of Lenin by the Soviet state, and one Order of the October Revolution and one Order of the Red Banner of Labour.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] During a state visit to Peru in the 1970s with Leonid Brezhnev and Andrei Gromyko, all three were awarded the Grand Cross of the Order of the Sun by President Francisco Morales Bermúdez.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] The Moscow State Textile University was named in his honour in 1981, in 1982 a bust to honour Kosygin was placed in Leningrad, present-day Saint Petersburg.
[src:alexei-kosygin/alexei-kosygin] In 2006 the Russian Government renamed a street after him.
